<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economy Not Doing Well: Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition United
Parties (UP) today said the ongoing strike by farm workers
reflects fundamental macro-economic problems the country is
currently facing.
</P>
<P>
UP Information and Publicity Secretary Isaac Manyemba told the
Zimbabwe National News Agency that commercial farmers, like
employers in other sectors, found it difficult to give workers
reasonable wage increments because of the ever soaring cost of
production, among other constraints.
</P>
<P>
"The real problem lies, by and large, neither with the
employer nor the employees but heavy taxation and high cost of
production leaves the employer with little room for wage
increments," he said.
</P>
<P>
The high budget deficit due to uncontrolled public
expenditure, he said, caused runaway inflation resulting in price
increases.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, workers find it difficult to survive hence the
widespread industrial actions," he said, adding that farm workers
are among the lowest paid in the country.
</P>
<P>
Many sectors of the economy were hit by strikes this year as
workers demanded higher wage and salary increases than those
offered by their employers.
</P>
<P>
And for the first time, commercial farm workers also went on
strike, demanding monthly wages of up to 848 Zimbabwe Dollars (67
U.S. Dollars), up from about 360 Zimbabwe Dollars (28 U.S.
Dollars), while farmers offered them a minimum wage of 460
Zimbabwe Dollars (36 U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
