<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kohl Faces Test at Party Congress in Leipzig </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leipzig, October 12 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
is facing a vital test at the ruling party national congress in
forging a united front for the next national elections in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day Christian Democratic Union (CDU) congress
opened here today, some senior CDU members criticized Kohl's
leadership while the party's junior members urged Kohl to step
down as CDU party leader after the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, 67, has been chairman of the CDU for 24 years and German
chancellor for uninterrupted 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Although most opinion polls had showed that his public support
was dropping down, Kohl announced in April that he would run for
an unparalleled fifth term of office.
</P>
<P>
Unpleasant with Kohl's monopoly of power over the past decades,
Klaus Escher, chairman of CDU's youth wing, last week made a
public call on Kohl to give up the party leadership after 1998,
saying that it was time for a "generational change."
</P>
<P>
Peter Mueller, CDU party chairman for the German state of
Saarland, also told the German Stern magazine that "there is an
increasing pressure for change at the top."
</P>
<P>
Despite the attacks from his own ranks, Kohl said today in an
interview with the Welt am Sonntag, a German newspaper, "We must
and will run the 1998 election campaigns with great solidarity."
</P>
<P>
He also definitely rejected the idea of giving up the party
leadership, remaining as the chancellor candidate of the CDU for
the next elections.
</P>
<P>
Past experiences had showed that such a division could produced
"miserable" results, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, noted that in order to avoid public rifts
and rally the 1,001 delegates firmly behind him, Kohl must deliver
a powerful speech at the congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He made at such a kind of speech at the 1994 Hamburg local CDU
congress, which successfully united his depressed party and
provided a fresh thrust for the CDU to win reelection in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Only a similar breakthrough will give the party new courage
and bring its members firmly behind him," said Welt am Sonntag
newspaper in a commentary today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
