<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Calls for Global Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today urged the international community to work more
actively to secure a just and viable solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
"I am optimist that if the international community is engaged
more decisively than in the past, the road towards a just,
workable and viable solution in Cyprus will open," said the
president in a message to a Greek Cypriot rally.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot demonstrators were protesting the occupation
by Turkey of Morphou village on the northwestern coast of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The president's message, read out by Justice and Public Order
Minister Nicos Koshis, reiterated the President's pledge that he
would not "allow the Turkish air force to bomb our towns and
villages at will, as it has done in the past, without being able
to defend ourselves."
</P>
<P>
It said Cyprus will continue to boost its air defense
capability until the threat emanating from the continuing Turkish
occupation ends.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government signed an agreement with Russia earlier
this year to buy an undisclosed number of S-300 surface-to-air
missiles. The missiles are expected to be deployed on the island
in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Reacting strongly to the missile deal, Turkey threatened a
preemptive strike against Cyprus if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus responded that it would not deploy the missiles if there
is sufficient progress toward a settlement or an agreement on the
demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the 37 percent of the island in the wake of a
failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
