<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-12 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Invited to Attend MENA Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today received an
invitation to attend the Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
Economic Conference due to be held in November in the Qatari
capital city of Doha, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was extended to Jordanian Minister of Foreign
Affairs Fayez Tarawneh by the Qatari Embassy in Amman, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has not officially responded to the
invitation today, but on September 23 the Arabic newspaper Al
Hayat quoted Tarawneh as saying that Jordan would attend the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference is to be held under the title of creating a new
partnership of trade and economic development between the public
and private sectors of Middle East and North Africa beyond the
year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has invited 92 countries and organizations to attend the
November 16 to 18 conference and expects some 2,900 foreign
participants for the conference, among them 800 government
delegates, 800 businessmen, 300 representatives of international
and regional organizations, 500 journalists, as well as 500 people
from the host country.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of Middle East, African and European
countries have been invited to attend the conference which was
boycotted by some Arab countries due to an expected Israeli
participation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will send its Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
the meeting while Israel will be represented by Foreign Minister
David Levy, they added.
</P>
<P>
The conference is traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel
and their major partners in the industrialized world. It is the
fourth since it was launched in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Though Qatar remained firm on hosting the conference as
scheduled, it had to downgrade the meeting from a summit to a
ministerial level, saying the current atmosphere is not
"appropriate" to invite heads of states because of the stalled
Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In protest against the deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace
process, Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian National Authority, the
United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia have announced that they
will boycott the conference.
</P>
<P>
Most of other Arab countries has not yet officially voiced
their stands, but observers here said that they would most likely
send delegates at low levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
