<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-12 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Says Netanyahu-Arafat Summit Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today telephoned Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to praise his meeting with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat last week as a "positive progress."
</P>
<P>
Albright said the Netanyahu-Arafat secret summit at the Erez
checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip in the small hours of
Wednesday is a step to advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process, according to Israeli Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
In September Albright made her maiden visit to the Middle East
as secretary of state to revive the peace process, which came to a
halt after Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem in March. Short of making a breakthrough, she
did manage to arrange a series of meetings between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Arafat summit, the first in eight months,
reportedly focused on ways to push forward the peace process. The
two leaders agreed to work together in a joint fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a weekly Cabinet meeting today, Netanyahu
praised the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) for making a
"good start" in recent days to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But he said the Palestinian efforts "should be examined
further to ensure that the fight will be systematic and ongoing,"
the Prime Minister's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai told the Cabinet that
negotiations on the opening of the Gaza International Airport
would be conducted within the framework of principles set by the
inner Cabinet formed by Netanyahu, Foreign Minister David Levy and
himself.
</P>
<P>
Israel maintains that it will retain security control over the
Gaza airport and seaport in order to prevent the smuggling in
weapons that could threaten Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the Gaza airport is one of the key interim
issues to be settled in the renewed peace negotiations, which will
tackle the "safe passages" between the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and the release of Palestinian prisoners from Israeli jails as
well.
</P>
<P>
In Cairo, the Egyptian English daily Al-Ahram today quoted
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa as criticizing the
Netanyahu-Arafat summit for failing to produce any tangible
results.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the summit did not tackle real issues, adding Egypt
wanted to see real movement and would not be convinced by
"handshakes and anything superficial."
</P>
<P>
His comments, contradicting those of Israel and the United
States, seemed to reflect Egypt's displeasure with the fact that
Egypt was sidelined in recent diplomatic activities to restart the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
