<HEADLINE> Arafat Receives Phone Call From Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 12 (Xinhua)--U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright made a phone call today to Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat, informing him
that the U.S. peace envoy will return to the region shortly.
</P>
<P>
According to the Palestinian News Agency WAFA, Arafat, who
received the phone call in Gaza, said that Albright also told him
that the U.S. side was satisfied with the progress made so far by
the PNA and Israel in preparation of the reopening of the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of State also highly appreciated his talks
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu earlier this week,
saying such talks were very helpful for bringing the peace
process back on track, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
With the help of U.S. Peace envoy Dennis Ross, Arafat
held a secret talk with Netanyahu on Wednesday at the Erez
Checkpoint between Jerusalem and Gaza and the two discussed ways
and means for reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Before that, nine joint committees appointed by the PNA and
Israel started their preparations on respective agendas that to
be discussed during the peace talks. The most important issues
include the security cooperation between the PNA and Israel,
definition of Jewish settlements, Israeli troop redeployment in
West Bank, the Gaza Airport and Seaport, and the safe
passage between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Ross will return to the region shortly to
help speed up the peace talk preparations, without giving a
definite date, Arafat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
