<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers' Strike to End Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of Kenyan
teachers are to end strike on Monday after the government has
agreed the up-to-200-percent pay hike over the next five years
starting from January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ambrose Adongo, chief of the 240,000-member Kenya National
Union of Teachers (KNUT), today called off the 12-day strike and
asked them to resume their duties at 8:00 a.m. on Monday, the
Kenyan News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Teachers go back to school, teachers go back to teach," he
said on Kenyan Television Network (KTN) evening news.
</P>
<P>
Adongo also declared that teachers around the country will
continue to give President Daniel arap Moi and the government
full support, noting that Moi is a founder of KNUT.
</P>
<P>
However, the strike is widely believed to hurt the ruling
Kenya African National Union (KANU) in the coming elections as
teachers, among the lowest paid professionals in Kenya, carry
considerable political influences especially in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The strike has forced more than seven million pupils out of
classrooms in primary and secondary schools since October 1 in a
key month for national examinations.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, a national holiday known as Moi Day, Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi appointed three senior government
officials to immediately meet with KNUT officials so as to end
the strike within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the national interest that the dispute be resolved
amicably and expeditiously," said Moi, 74 and in power since
1978. He is widely believed to win the general election which
will be called by himself later this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government argued that the 200-percent pay rise
demand by KNUT is unacceptable as it means more than half of the
government expenditure, nearly 90 billion Shillings (1.47 billion
U.S. Dollars), should be used on teachers' pay alone.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' pay makes up 16 percent of the entire government
expenditure in this east African country in the 1997-1998 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
A Kenyan primary teacher in the bottom rung currently earns
only about 1,800 Shillings (29 Dollars) per month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
