<HEADLINE> Israel to Attend MENA Economic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Ministry
confirmed today that Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy is due
to head Israel's team to attend the Middle East and North Africa
Economic Conference to be held in Qatar next month.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation is to include Finance Minister Yaacov
Neeman and some business leaders, who will seek ways to
boost economic cooperation with other countries of the region
during the meeting which is scheduled from November 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
Sumir Raveh, the head of Israel trade mission in Doha
said that he has not received Qatari invitation but he said
Qatar has announced it would invite Levy and actually the
invitation is just formality.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry also expressed satisfaction that the
United States has applied pressure on Arab states not to
call off the conference.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries have privately asked Qatar to cancel or
at least postpone the conference because of the deadlock in
the Middle East peace process, which, they said, was caused by the
hard-line policy of current Israeli Likud-government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some Arab countries, including Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirate, have announced they would boycott
the Doha meeting.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the appeal from Arab world, Qatar has downgraded
the meeting from a summit to a conference at a ministerial
level. And it started Tuesday sending out invitations to the
conference to about 92 countries and international organizations
and said it has no plans to delay it.
</P>
<P>
"The conference will be held as scheduled and preparations
for it are proceeding in the desired fashion," Qatar's Foreign
Ministry spokesman Fawza bin Ahmad al-Attiyah said today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
