<HEADLINE> Teenager Drug Distributors Arouse Concern in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The use of teenagers for the
distribution of dangerous drugs and illicit substances in Nigeria
has aroused concern of the National Drug Law Enforcement Agency
(NDLEA), local press said today.
</P>
<P>
Teenagers are mostly recruited from primary and secondary
schools by drug dealers, according to NDLEA Chairman
Major-General Musa Bamaiyi, who did not give the number of the
teenagers involved.
</P>
<P>
He however disclosed that some of the teenagers had already
been apprehended and were being detained at various NDLEA cells
nationwide, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
NDLEA had also intensified efforts to track those who lure the
youths into such nefarious trade, Bamaiyi said over the weekend
at a NDLEA train-the-trainers workshop held in Kaduna state,
north Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"No responsible government can afford to fold its arms and
watch these unscrupulous and negligible percentage of Nigerians
destroy the populace at home and bring disrepute to the nation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
While calling on all tiers of government to join hands
together in the drug war, Bamaiyi urged the trainers to
collaborate with NDLEA in the prevention of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
"We have realized that prevention is not only better but also
cheaper than cure," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
