<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Urged to Punish Sexual Harassment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has been advised to review the law to punish people involved in
harassing women at work places.
</P>
<P>
Presently cases of sexual harassment at places of work have
surged but there are no clauses in the proposed employment law,
whose first draft is expected to be ready next January, to
protect women against such acts.
</P>
<P>
The advice was made during the four-day workshop of the
Tanzania Industrial Relations Association on the proposed
Employment Act 1997 and the issue of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which ended Saturday, pointed out that the
proposed Act had omitted the issue of safeguarding workers in
respect of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
The participants urged the government not to abandon its role
in regulating and supervising the labor market in order to
maintain harmonious labor relations for increased productivity.
</P>
<P>
On expanding private and multinational companies, they advised
the Ministry of Labor to ensure workers are not underpaid or
harassed.
</P>
<P>
The workshop earlier accused some private companies and
multinationals of exploiting workers by underpaying or denying
rights and compensations because of lack of proper labor ministry
supervision.
</P>
<P>
The delegates discussed several parts of the proposed act
which discriminates women, and recommended that the restriction
of employment of women in mines and night work should be removed
so as to offer fair treatment to all people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
