<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-12 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aida Celebrates 125th Birthday in Egypt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Verdi's Aida, the love story that
has fascinated opera lovers in the past 125 years, sparked new
fantasy as the best sopranos sang their high notes under the stars
in front of Egypt's ancient pharaohs and VIPs from the world.
</P>
<P>
Hailed as the most lavish production ever of Aida, the
performance is intended to celebrate the 125th anniversary of
Aida's premiere in Cairo and the 75th anniversary of the discovery
of the Tomb of King Tutankhamun.
</P>
<P>
The opera, chanting the doomed love between an ancient Egyptian
conqueror and an Ethiopian slave girl, was commissioned from Verdi
by the Khedive Ismail to mark the opening of the Suez Canal in
1869 but its debut was delayed for three years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, eager to promote its image as a safe tourist paradise,
has put in 15 million pounds to produce the opera and has staged
an enormous media campaign to sell tickets since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Up to 18,000 opera fans, including wives of several world
leaders, are attracted to the event staged in front of the
3,000-year-old Temple of Queen Hatshepsut on the west bank of the
Nile opposite Luxor, about 700 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Luxor, meaning "the palaces" in Arabic, is the most
awe-inspiring conglomeration of ancient monuments in the world.
</P>
<P>
Giving a finishing touch to months of laborious preparation,
the world's leading Verdi sopranos, Aprile Milo and Velhelmnia
Fernandez, shared the title role, while tenors Guiseppe Giaccomini
and Walter Fraccaro played Radames, Aida's lover.
</P>
<P>
All tickets of the inaugural performance were sold out while
the booking of other performances ranged between 60-70 percent.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of the expected crowds a temporary theater
seating 5,000 has been constructed and a new lighting system
installed along the road leading to the temple.
</P>
<P>
To improve security, 300 Feddans of sugar-cane that used to
grow along the roads leading to the venue have been razed to the
ground. Sugar cane plantations are well-known hideouts of Islamist
militants who often carry out terrorist raids on tourists.
</P>
<P>
Officials hope the six-night run will attract a record number
of visitors despite last month's deadly bombing of a German
tourist bus in front of the Egyptian Museum in downtown Cairo.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Culture Farouk Hosni, the six nights
of performances between October 12-17 constitute a "most important
artistic event reflecting the glory of Egyptian civilization."
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak, who sat among the thousands of viewers
in the open-air theater tonight, has ordered the opera to be
performed annually on the same location to give an impetus to
Egypt's tourist industry as well as artistic and cultural
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
