<HEADLINE> Africa's Largest Art Event Opens in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Second Johannesburg
Biennial, said to be the most important contemporary art event on
the African continent, opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Besides an exhibition of contemporary art, the 99-day event
also includes performances, a film program featuring African
movies, an international conference on the definition of
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
In addition, people will see various alternative installations
ranging from billboards, bus shelters, bars and restaurants to
TV, radio and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
An official opening ceremony was held this evening in Newtown,
downtown Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Johannesburg Mayor Isaac Mogase, Director of United Nations
Education, Science and Cultural Organization in South Africa,
Louis Honwana, South African Constitutional Court Judge Albic
Sachs and Director-General of South Africa's Department of Arts,
Culture, Science and Technology, Roger Jardine, were present at
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Jardine told the ceremony that the event will create a
momentum to re-generate the urban development of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Besides Johannesburg, Cape Town is another venue for the
Biennial.
</P>
<P>
The Biennial, under the theme of "Trade Routes: History and
Geography", attracted some 160 artists from more than 60
countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
The first Biennial took place in 1995 when South Africa was
emerging from decades of cultural isolation in the apartheid era.
</P>
