<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Promote Wheat Production: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will take measures to
promote wheat production to realize 75 percent self-sufficiency by
the year 2000, Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
said today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Economic Committee of the ruling National
Democratic Party, he said that the government will pay the wheat
growers a price one third higher than the average international
prices next year.
</P>
<P>
Farmers, now receiving about 71 pounds (about 21 dollars) per
ardeb (197.6 liters), will get 95 pounds (about 28 dollars) in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Farmers turned in about 1.3 million tonnes of wheat this year,
an increase of 300,000 tonnes over last year, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Food and Agriculture Organization, Egypt's
self-sufficiency in wheat reached 57 percent in 1995. But it did
not give the percentage of 1996 or 1997, while predicting that
Egypt will be self-sufficient in food within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said the prospects also augur well for
Egyptian non-petroleum exports, which registered a 15 percent
increase in the first half of this year and the last six months of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Exports of manufactured goods, notably spinning and textiles,
registered an increase of 29 percent during the same period, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili said the government is aiming to raise the value of
cotton export next year to more than 3 billion pounds (about 900
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
He expected that next year will witness an increase in exports
of rice, spinning and weaving, vegetables and fruits and food
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0028 </DOCNO>
