<HEADLINE> Israeli Military Chief Starts Visit to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Forces Chief of
Staff Amnon Shahak arrived here today on a three-day visit to
Turkey aimed at enhancing bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Shahak will hold talks Monday with his Turkish counterpart
Ismail Hakki Karaday and other high-ranking military officers.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Israeli military chief will also meet
with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
He is reportedly to persuade the Turkish military to replace
its armored units with Israeli-made Merkava 3 tanks, which are one
of the world's most advanced types.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to discuss the date and other
specific arrangements concerning scheduled three-way naval
maneuvers of Israel, Turkey and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite war games, re-scheduled to start on November 16,
might be further delayed until next January at the request of the
U.S. side, earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's involvement in the joint exercises has been strongly
criticized by the Arab world, which accused Ankara of betraying
the interests of Muslims by developing closer military ties with
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed two defense and military training
agreements last year to allow joint warplane exercises in each
other's airspace.
</P>
<P>
Shahak's tour, a return visit for the one to Israel by Karaday
last February, indicates that the two countries are determined to
boost their cooperation in the military field, observers here
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
