<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-12 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Holds Talks with Main Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
held talks with the main anti-government group, the Sudan People's
Liberation Movement, the local daily Akhbar el Yom reported today.
</P>
<P>
A Sudanese minister of state John Dor Magok said that the talks
were held during October 5 to 9 in Germany, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Movement, led by John Garang, along with other rebel
factions, began in early 1980's to fight against the government
for an independent state in the south.
</P>
<P>
John Dor Magok, head of the government delegation, described
the talks as "positive" and would give "strong push" for the
success of the upcoming negotiations in Kenyan capital Nairobi on
October 28.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted him as saying that the two sides had come to
a conclusion that "there is no option but dialogue as a way to
resolving differences between the two parties."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Sudanese President Omar Bashir said today to a
rally in Juba, a southern city about 1,230 kilometers from
Khartoum, that his government was determined to pursue peace in
the south of the country, Sudanese News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the accord signed by the government and six rebel
factions had "established peace" for the country, safeguarding
rights and obligations of all citizens without discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government and rebel factions signed last April an
agreement, under which self-determination will be exercised in the
south after a transitional period of four years.
</P>
<P>
But the agreement was rejected by the People's Movement led
by John Garang.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a Kenyan envoy is expected to visit
Uganda, Ethiopia and Eritrea, which are mediating between the
Sudanese government and the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
After the tour, the envoy will come to Khartoum to meet with
Sudanese officials, helping arrange the talks between the Sudanese
government and the rebel factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
