<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Negotiations Across Taiwan Straits Urged (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The peaceful reunification of China is a complicated process
and something that cannot be done overnight. Political
negotiations between the two sides should come in different
stages, starting with an end to the long-lasting hostilities. This
is the desire of people on both sides and an important part of
developing cross-straits relations.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, in his eight-point proposals, suggested
negotiations as a first step in "formally putting an end to
hostilities under the One China principle".
</P>
<P>
The two side should shoulder the responsibility of safeguarding
Chinese sovereignty and territorial integrity and work out plans
for future development of cross-Straits ties. By doing so a safe
environment will be created for developing cross-Straits ties, and
the question of the vital interests of Taiwan compatriots will be
tackled, and a plan will be worked out for further developing
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan side, however, refused Jiang's proposal of formally
ending cross-strait hostilities under the principle of One China,
in January of 1995. Then, when bilateral relations grew strained
in mid-1995 because of reasons known to all, Taiwan expressed a
desire to deal with the issue of cross-Straits hostilities and
said it would give priority to ending hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Recently, important people in Taiwan have made it clear that
political issues can be discussed and that the most important is
to end cross-Straits hostilities and sign peace agreements, but
some people in Taiwan are against this.
</P>
<P>
Whether cross-Straits political negotiations can be held or not
is a question of sincerity rather than rhetoric and the impasse in
cross-Straits negotiations will be broken if both sides have good
faith, and strive for a consensus with a rational and pragmatic
attitude in the following points:
</P>
<P>
First, the One China principle must be adhered to. This is
directed at those in Taiwan and elsewhere who attempt to separate
Taiwan from China. So, negotiations on routine matters should
follow this principle, and political ones should follow it even
more.
</P>
<P>
The Association for Relations across the Taiwan Straits has
always maintained that both sides should be clear in adhering to
the One China principle in negotiations on routine matters, but
political implications can be left for future negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Negotiations Across Taiwan Straits Urged (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The political meaning of "One China" is, as Jiang Zemin made it
clear in his speech on January 30, 1995, that there is only one
China, and Taiwan is part of it. China's sovereignty and
territorial integration are one and China opposes any "Taiwan
Independence" activity or any advocating "Splitting and Separate
Ruling" or "Having Two Chinas for the Time-being".
</P>
<P>
To safeguard the interests of the Chinese nation as a whole the
two sides should adhere to the One China principle, and if the
Taiwan side insists on "Recognizing the Republic of China" as the
prerequisite for holding political negotiations between the two
sides, it is an attempt to make two Chinas.
</P>
<P>
The mainland has, from the very beginning, made it clear that
negotiations between the CPC and the Kuomintang are "negotiations
between equal parties", and Jiang Zemin, in his Eight-Point
Proposals said that the location and methods of political
negotiations could be settled through talks.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the mainland has insisted on equal negotiations
under the One China principle, and has never meant to have a
"central-to-locality" attitude, and has fully understood the
thinking and situation of Taiwan, in order to avoid causing it any
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, in his report to the 15th CPC National Congress,
said, "Under the prerequisite of One China, any issue can be
discussed, and any comment and proposal, if it is helpful to the
reunification of the motherland, can be put forward."
</P>
<P>
No foreign forces can interfere in political negotiations
between the two sides because the reunification of the two is an
internal affair of China and should be resolved by the people of
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
History has shown that wherever there has been foreign
interference, the Taiwan question has gotten even more critical
and complicated, and the reunification process was
interrupted. But, the mainland's door has always been open to
political negotiations between the two sides, and the earlier the
talks, the better.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
