<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok Approves Rescue Plan for Ailing Finance Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors can invest in
Thai finance companies as a major shareholder as a means to put
the 58 suspended finance firms on the road of recovery, according
to a press release of the Thai Government House today.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners will be allowed to hold more than 50 percent of the
shares in financial companies for up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
However, after 10 years, any increase of fund must be sold to
Thai shareholders only, until the foreign shareholding is reduced
to less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting today, the Economic Affairs Screening Committee
also approved that the amount of non-performing loans of the
finance firms can be deducted for taxation.
</P>
<P>
Those of the 58 suspended finance firms which will submit plans
for rehabilitation are required to have enough money to raise
fund.
</P>
<P>
They can raise fund by themselves, seeking a new partner, by
acquisition or merging. Each finance company must have a fund
ratio no less than 15 percent of capital adequacy ratio.
</P>
<P>
They can also be acquired by, or merged with, other finance
company, with the latter as the core institution.
</P>
<P>
The 58 finance companies were suspended by the government in
June and August because of their huge amounts of bad and
non-performing debts and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is under pressure of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) to restructure its financial sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
