<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Turkish Violations of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has made
representations to the United Nations and the International Civil
Aviation Organization over the violations of Cypriot airspace by
Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Cyprus today said that two Turkish
fighter planes flew over the Paphos area in the western part of
the island on Sunday, and took pictures of the Paphos military
airport in construction.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish warplanes tangled with two Greek fighter bombers,
which were taking part in an ongoing joint exercise with Cyprus
troops, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the Cyprus Ministry of Foreign Affairs made
the necessary representations to the U.N. and the International
Civil Aviation Organization, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish violations took place when the Cyprus National
Guard is carrying out an exercise, in which Greek warplanes and
warships are participating.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 60 Turkish warplanes on Sunday flew into the
airspace over the southeastern Aegean Sea between Cyprus and the
Greek islands of Crete and Rhodes, where Greek troops are carrying
out an exercise.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took the
northern third of the Mediterranean island following a failed coup
by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1984 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus", which is recognized only by Turkey,
against the internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
