<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Negotiations Across Taiwan Straits Urged (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The October issue of Beijing's
"Cross-Straits Relations Monthly" has called for early political
negotiations between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
In an article titled "Starting Early Political Negotiations to
Promote the Development of Cross-Straits Relations", it says that
Jiang Zemin, General Secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), spoke about peaceful reunification
in his political report to the 15th CPC National Congress last
month.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that as a first step, the two sides of the Taiwan
Straits can hold negotiations on ending cross-Straits hostilities
under the "One China" principle, and said he hopes that Taiwan
will respond to this seriously and hold political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Qian Qichen also said recently that he hopes the
Taiwan authorities will exchange views with the mainland on a
agenda for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
This is an important decision of the CPC and the Chinese
government for promoting the development of cross-Straits
relations, peacefully removing political differences between the
two, and speeding up peaceful reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
This shows the breadth of vision, practical manner, and great
sincerity and determination of the CPC Central Committee, and it
reflects the aspirations of the people on both sides of the
Straits, who hope to end hostilities as soon as possible by
improving and developing cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
This has gotten a warm response from Taiwan compatriots and
attracted the concern of the international community and Taiwan
should respond to the call seriously and begin negotiations with
the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Negotiations Across Taiwan Straits Urged (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The only way to solve differences and develop cross-Straits
relations, and promote peaceful reunification of the motherland is
political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The new century is characterized by both opportunities and
challenges and the Chinese people are looking forward to ending
cross-Straits hostilities as soon as possible. This will lead to
common prosperity of the two economies and the gradual development
of peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the mainland has adjusted its policies
on political negotiations in keeping with developments and changes
in cross-Straits relations in the following ways:
</P>
<P>
First, there has been a change in participants. The
negotiations used to be primarily a CPC and Kuomintang affair, but
then turned into negotiations with other participants, and finally
came to be defined as cross-Straits political negotiations set by
Jiang Zemin in his eight-point proposals.
</P>
<P>
Second, there has been a change in the content of the
negotiations. The 1979 "Letters to Taiwan Compatriots" proposed an
end to military hostilities across the Taiwan Straits. Then, the
report to the 14th CPC National Congress proposed a formal halt to
cross-Straits hostilities and a step-by-step peaceful
reunification. Jiang Zemin then offered the eight-point proposals,
stipulating that, as a first step, the two sides can begin
negotiations on the issue of formally ending cross-Straits
hostilities under the One China principle.
</P>
</TEXT>
