<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing Offshore Natural Gas Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Developing natural gas has
helped China adjust its energy structure and increase the supply
of high-quality energy from offshore areas, Zhao Xiuguang, of the
China National Offshore Oil Corporation, told the 15th World
Petroleum Congress in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
For a long time, the use of coal caused problems for the
environment and transport in coastal areas, and it needed to be
replaced by clean and efficient natural gas to meet the needs of
continued economic expansion, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The western part of the South China Sea is a key gas source and
four oilfields and 15 gas-bearing structures have been found there.
</P>
<P>
The Nanyacheng-131 oilfield off the island province of Hainan
now provides 2.9 billion cu.m. of natural gas for the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region annually via a 780-km submarine
pipeline, and 500 million cu.m. of gas for the province's
fertilizer plants and power plants via a 100-km pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that the western sea area of the South China Sea will
add three billion cu.m. of gas by the year 2005, and another three
billion cu.m. by 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing Offshore Natural Gas Areas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two oilfields and eight oil-bearing structures have been
discovered in the eastern part of the South China Sea. The Pinghu
oilfield, about 400 km east of Shanghai, is being developed and
will supply the city with 400 million cu.m. of gas every year, and
add 1.2 billion cu.m. of gas by 2010.
</P>
<P>
On the Bohai sea, one oilfield and 18 oil-bearing structures
have been discovered. The Jinzhou-202 oilfield provides 400
million cu.m. of natural gas for the Jinzhou Chemical Fertilizer
Plant annually and will increase the supply to 700 million
cu.m. by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and the provinces of Guangdong, Fujian, Zhejiang, and
Jiangsu are the most economically-vibrant regions in China, with a
13 to 19 percent annual increase on average in their GDPs, far
exceeding the national average. Their combined energy demand will
be nearly 360 million tons of coal by the year 2000, 470 million tons
by 2005, and 610 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
So, developing offshore natural gas is important for sustained
economic growth in the region, Zhao pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
