<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Records Fall at China's National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Teenager Chen Yan broke the
15-year-old world record in the women's 400-meter individual
medley, highlighting the opening day competitions of the Eighth
National Games here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chen, 16, stole the limelight by clocking four minutes and
34.79 seconds, crushing the previous mark of 4:36.10 set by Petra
Schneider of former East Germany on August 1, 1982.
</P>
<P>
World record holder and Olympic champion Le Jingyi clocked the
year best of 54.10 seconds to take the first swimming title of the
Games in the women's 100-meter freestyle, an event she won in the
Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
Chen signalled the advent of the Chinese younger swimmers who
are ready to take over the torch from the veterans.
</P>
<P>
"She was chased very hard by second-placer Wu Yanyan of Guangxi
Autunomous Region, and she had to strike out for the gold, which
probably was the factor for her record," said coach Han Bingyan.
</P>
<P>
"I had not expected to set a new world mark," said Chen. "But I
have trained hard after I returned home from Atlanta."
</P>
<P>
Being the best short-course women swimmer in the world, as her
coach Zhou Ming said, Le Jingyi was very elated to see the new
swimmers have getting more mature.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely congratulate Chen Yan on her world mark," Le said.
"I hope the young swimmers will have better performances in the
international competitions."
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100-meter breaststroke, Guangdong's Zeng Qiliang,
who finished seventh in the Atlanta Games, won the gold with a
Asian-mark of one minute and 1.66 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200-meter freestyle gold was taken by Shanghai's Chen
Zhou, followed by Tianjin's Du Jie and Hebei's Deng Qingsong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese strongwomen also launched their strong attacks upon
the world records as a total of 12 women lifters surpassed the
listed records in the first-day competitions.
</P>
<P>
Xing Fen of Guangdong province, claimed three world best marks
en route to her victory in the women's 46-kg category, by lifting
85 kgs in snatch and 117.5 kgs in jerk for a combined total of
202.5 kgs.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhuo of Liaoning province, repeated the feat with three
world best scores to take the women's 50-kg title in a two-lift
combined total of 217.5 kgs.
</P>
<P>
The previous world marks in the 46-kg class were 81.5 kgs in
snatch, 105.5 kgs in jerk for a total of 185 kgs while the 50-kg
class world records were 88 kgs in snatch, 110.5 kgs in jerk and
197.5 kgs in two-lift total.
</P>
<P>
Four other women surpassed all three marks in the 46-kg class,
and two others bettered all three records in the 50-kg category.
</P>
<P>
Markswomen Zhao Ying and Xu Yimin both improved the world
record of 596 by one point in the women's standard rifle prone
competition.
</P>
<P>
The previous mark was set by Irina Shilova of former Soviet
Union on August 15, 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
