<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Integration into World Economy Benefits All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The furthering of China's
integration into the world economy will benefit both China and its
 partners, a Chinese businesswoman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Shi Xiaoyuan, executive vice president of China National
Chemicals Imports and Exports Corporation (Sinochem), told a
plenary session of the East Asia Economic Summit that Sinochem's
annual business turnover has averaged 13.7 billion U.S. dollars
since 1988 compared with a total growth of less than 3 billion
dollars over a period of 38 years from 1950 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
She attributed the rapid growth in the past decade to the
company's strategic readjustment in 1988 when Sinochem began to go
 global.
</P>
<P>
Today, Sinochem is no longer a mere trading company. It has
diversified into manufacturing, finance, shipping, real estate and
 insurance, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Sinochem has 46 domestic subsidiaries and
five overseas regional groups which control 44 overseas
subsidiaries in 22 countries and regions, she added.
</P>
<P>
At the session, a U.S. scholar attending the session said that
when China is further integrated into the world economy, its
increasing export ability will be a threat to the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
Shi responded that the integration of China into the world
economy will not pose a threat to the rest of the world. On the
contrary, it will benefit the world because China will further
open its markets to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
China will open up wider in the future and that will obviously
offer a lot of opportunities for the businessmen of the world, she
 said.
</P>
<P>
At two other plenary sessions held in parallel earlier today,
top officials from Chongqing, China's newly established
municipality directly under the central government, and Hainan,
the largest special economic zone in China, explained their
preferential policies and excellent services to attract overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of Chongqing to be China's 4th municipality has
provided excellent opportunities for entrepreneurs and merchants
of the world to increase economic cooperation with the city, said
Xu Zhongmin, vice mayor of Chongqing, an economic center on the
upper reaches of the 6,300-km Yangtze River, the longest in China.
</P>
<P>
Both Chongqing and Hainan have decided to take measures to
encourage foreign investment, which include the formulation of
laws and regulations, strict enforcement of laws to protect the
legal rights and interests of foreign investors, adoption of one
stop service to raise efficiency, control of land price and
complete opening of markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
