<HEADLINE> New York Harbor Increases Cargo Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Cargo traffic handled by New
York Harbor rose about 12 percent in the first half of this year
compared with the same period 1996 due to a healthy economy and
infrastructure improvement, Port Authority reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Traffic increases were seen in evenly split imports and
exports, mostly in consumer goods including electrical and
electronics and cars, it said.
</P>
<P>
On the geographic scene, the growth came from almost every part
of the globe with Latin America leading the way, recording a 21
percent surge over last year, followed by Europe, up 15 percent,
Africa 13 percent and Mediterranean countries 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of containers moving through the port rose 11.8
percent to 832,499, a significant jump never seen in years.
</P>
<P>
The port has poured 500 million U.S. dollars in docks'
modernization in the past five years, including a ship-to-rail
terminal which helped cut the import and export costs.
</P>
<P>
Port officials said they need to do more to face the challenge
of growing cargos from East Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
