<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Prefers French Missiles to U.S. Stinger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Defense Ministry
announced today that it had decided to purchase French-made
Mistral portable missiles rather than U.S. Stinger or British
Starburst missiles.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 Mistral systems, valued at 250 billion won (275
million U.S. dollars), will be imported between 1998-1999 to
enhance the army's local air defense capabilities, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
It was a rare victory for France in South Korea, whose military
arsenal consists mainly of U.S.-made weapons.
</P>
<P>
France had offered to transfer missile technology to win the
fierce three-country bidding war, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
All three missiles met South Korean demands, but what won South
Korea over to Paris was the purchase terms, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Mistrals are more expensive, but more accurate, with a
successful hit rate of 92 percent, French officials in Seoul said.
</P>
<P>
As the army has already been operating about 1,000 Mistrals
imported in the late 1980s, the projected missile system has
advantage over Stinger and Starburst in terms of logistical
support, education, training and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
Washington had lobbied forcefully for Seoul to purchase Stinger
missiles, which American forces stationed here are armed with.
</P>
<P>
In early June, the Pentagon notified the U.S. Congress that
Seoul would purchase Stinger missiles. The Pentagon announced
plans to sell 1,065 Stinger missiles, plus launchers and support
equipment to the country.
</P>
<P>
But the South Korean Defense Ministry immediately denied this,
saying nothing had been decided and the ministry had simply
requested the United States to provide prices and related
documents.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said at that time that the final decision would be
made in July, but it was delayed amid heated lobbying by the three
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
