<HEADLINE> Israeli President Denies Remarks on Golan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President's Office
today denied a report quoting President Ezer Weizman as saying
that Israel is ready to give up Golan Heights in order to resume
peace talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The President's Office was commenting on a report published
on the leading Hebrew daily Yediot Ahronot, which claimed that
Weizman had hinted to United States President Bill Clinton
during his visit to Washington last week that Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu was ready to give up the occupied Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
The office said Weizman did not talk about territorial
compromise during his meeting with Clinton, but focused on ways
to resume peace talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Arye Shumer, Director-General of the President's Office,
charged Israeli Ambassador to the U.S. Eliyahu Ben-Elisa for
leaking the news about Weizman-Clinton talks. His office has
lodged complaints to the Foreign Ministry and Cabinet Secretary
Danny Naveh.
</P>
<P>
Eitan Ben-Tsur, Director-General of the Foreign Ministry, said
it was not the job of embassy officials to make statements on
the president's visit. He called the incident as a serious
offense and a deviation from the work of the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Weizman is to hold a meeting with Netanyahu either today or
Tuesday to brief the latter on his visit to Washington, which
focused on resumption of the peace process, not only with the
Palestinian National Authority, but also with with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Despite of being the ceremonial head of state, Weizman has
been outspoken about politics, especially on the government's
policies on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He is often at odds with the prime minister over
controversial remarks he made to foreign guests that revealed
their differences over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace process has been suspended since
early last year following a wave of suicide bombings launched
by Islamic militants and the access to power in May last year by
the hardline Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly called for unconditional resumption of
peace talks, but Syria insists that the talks should be
restarted from the point where they were left off last year with
the previous Labor government, namely a promise to fully
withdraw troops from the strategic Golan Heights taken by Israel
in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged deadlock in the peace track has led to fears
about possible armed confrontation between the two sides, and
Israel charges Damascus for preparing for a military attack
against Israel aimed at forcing the resumption of peace
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
