<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Adapt Rapidly Changing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti today said there is an urgent need for African countries
"to adapt to the rapidly changing information technology as a
tool of communication" in a bid to confront the challenge of
economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing the opening session of the Third
International Advertizing Association Africa Congress held here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti who is also the Minister for Planning and National
Development pointed out that with the process of globalization
gaining momentum, the economic marginalization of the African
continent was set to grow.
</P>
<P>
In the past, he noted, Africa had failed to take full
advantage of the opportunities offkred by growth in international
trade, inter-dependent enterprise and information technology.
</P>
<P>
The continent had also failed to take advantage of the
investment and financial flows to developing countries, the
vice-president added.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti stated that African countries were making efforts to
counter the economic marginalization of the@gontinent by
strengthening sub-regional groups.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these efforts, the Kenyan leader called upon
international organizations and bilateral donors to spearhead
efforts for finding a solution to the debt burden of the
continent on a "concerted basis".
</P>
<P>
He also required the international community to provide access
to the markets in the developed countries of processed goods from
developing countries, especially the African countries.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president stressed that African countries should make
use of information technology "to effectively advertize our
potentials to the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
In his view, the African continent has enormous amount of
resource and inexhaustible manpower that can steer it into a
newly industrializing continent and a commercial powerhouse in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the four-day congress due to end on October 16,
is "Creating a Borderless Continent: Africa's 21st Century
Communication Challenge".
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting noted that communication in Africa is
yet to be developed as governments in the continent still find it
expensive to spend on infrastructure like roads, railway lines,
telephone networks and rural electrification.
</P>
<P>
Many African governments are also reluctant to liberalize the
information industry so that private enterprises can invest and
develop the industry, they said. Endite

