<HEADLINE> WPC Delegates Seek Western Aid With Capital, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the 15th World
Petroleum Congress (WPC) today strongly appealed
to western industrialized countries to offer substantive aid in
capital and technology to tap petroleum resources.
</P>
<P>
"African countries face capital problems in opening up local
petroleum resources, so the western petroleum powers should
provide support in this effort," said Abba Kantao, head of the
Mali delegation to the WPC in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Some developed countries have repeatedly said they would help
us exploit oil resources, but we hope that the promises can be
carried out in earnest," said Kantao, who is Mali's director of
geology and minerals.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum industries in many developing countries have
remained stagnant because of insufficient funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Driven by interests, the western countries may go and invest
in some developing nations," said Leite Da Costa of Angola, "but
they did little in technological transfer."
</P>
<P>
After a long civil war, Angola needs full-scale reconstruction,
he said, adding that petroleum is the country's most important
source of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The African delegate expressed his hope that developed
countries would make an effort to promote technological transfer
and seek common development.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 4,000 delegates from more than 90 countries and regions
are attending the five-day conference, which will focus on "Technology
and Globalization -- Leading the Petroleum Industry in the 21st
Century." 
