<HEADLINE> Action Urged to Save Mediterranean Fisheries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature
(WWF) is urging a European Union (EU) official to convince
Mediterranean states that they must take effective measures to
save their 3.8 billion U.S. dollars fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The WWF, along with Greenpeace and 41 Mediterranean
environmental groups, today called on Emma Bonino, the EU
commissioner for fishery and consumer policies, to increase
efforts on behalf of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The 22nd Session of the General Fisheries Council for the
Mediterranean (GFCM) of the Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) of the United Nations opened in Rome today.
</P>
<P>
But the the European Commission's initiative for better
management of Mediterranean fish stocks Sea risks running aground
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The main bottleneck is lack of political will by GFCM member
states, says a press release from the WWF European Policy Office
in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
It says that crucial issues which must be resolved include the
overriding obligation to conserve marine species and ecosystems of
the Mediterranean, and the effective management of fishing
activities on a precautionary basis.
</P>
<P>
"The European Commission has an important responsibility in
ensuring that the Mediterranean governments, particularly EU
member states, will take the tough yet necessary management
decision to set Mediterranean fisheries on the course towards
sustainability," said Demetres Karavellas, WWF's Mediterranean
Fisheries Coordinator.
</P>
<P>
The release also quoted Bonino as saying that for the
Mediterranean, a policy of overfishing today will mean no fish
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The population of adult blue-fin tuna in the Mediterranean and
the East Atlantic has decreased by 83 percent in the last 20
years, while fleet expansion continues at an average annual rate
of 4 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The EU fleets account for most of the annual Mediterranean fish
catch of 1.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The GFCM was established in 1949, but it has so far failed to
introduce effective fisheries management. The Rome meeting will
determine the future role of GFCM as an effective management body,
and test the ability of the European Commission in motivating its
member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
