<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Trade Growing between Asia and Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Oil trading between Asia and
Africa has heated up because of the soaring demand for petroleum
in rapidly growing Asian countries, one senior oil official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Dirk van der Meer, president of the World Petroleum Congress
(WPC), told Xinhua in the ongoing WPC's 15th congress that Africa,
a continent with rich hydrocarbon resources, will play a more
important role in the world oil market.
</P>
<P>
Except for established oil-producing countries such as
Nigeria, Tunisia, Algeria and Libya, more African countries are
joining the oil development team, he said.
</P>
<P>
Van der Meer said the oil output in Africa in 1996 totaled 350
million tons, an increase of 1.5 percent from 1995. "The
production accounted for 10.4 percent of the world's total," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The daily oil output in Cote D'Ivoire averaged 2,055 tons last
year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1992, the proven oil reserves in Chad reached 200
million tons. The daily crude oil output of the country is
expected to top 20,550 tons in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Van der Meer said that Africa has already become the world's
second largest oil export region behind Gulf countries, and "the
export is expected to go upward in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asian countries and regions have realized the
importance of Africa in future oil supply. In the last five
years, oil exports from Africa to Asia doubled with the daily
amount averaging 61,650 tons, or 10 percent of Africa's total
daily production.
</P>
<P>
Van der Meer said more Asian petroleum companies in recent
years have turned to Africa to import oil. The Republic of Korea
last year imported 2,055 tons a day from Africa, becoming one of
the main traders in the Nigerian oil market.
</P>
<P>
Now the second largest African crude oil buyer, India Oil
Corporation has increased its daily crude import from Nigeria
to 50,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
