<HEADLINE> Pakistan Denies Reported Wheat Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Official sources here denied
today the reported wheat shortage in Pakistan, saying that there
is no wheat crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that there is adequate wheat stock available
in the four provinces to meet the domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent reports in the local press about the
wheat crisis, the sources said the government is fully alive to
the situation, and there is no question of any crisis.
</P>
<P>
All possible measures are being taken to check wheat shortage,
and the four provinces have enough wheat stock to meet the demand,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
They also said the provinces are building their reserves, as
more supply is in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that supply from the major sources of
imported wheat like the U.S., Canada and Australia is on
uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has so far procured 2.8 million tons
of wheat besides an import of 1.7 million tons. A total of 4.5
million tons of wheat have been made available so far, which is
1.2 million tons more than last year's supply.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Pakistan will import another 2.8
million tons of wheat up to March 1998 and its uninterrupted
supply will continue to the provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
