<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Eliminate Leprosy by Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
launch an action program next year for eliminating leprosy with
the aim to make the country free from the disease by the year
2000, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Free medical treatment for victims of the disease will be
provided in some public health centers in the country," Health
Minister Dr. Sujudi said today at an inter-country consultative
meeting of program managers on the elimination of leprosy held in
Surabaya, East Java, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) is ready to provide strong
support to Indonesia through its program, the minister said.
Indonesia has almost 34,000 leprosy sufferers and ranks the third
in the world after India and brazil, Sujudi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the success of the Indonesian leprosy elimination
program is due to the assistance of WHO and donor agencies from
several countries.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Noordin from WHO said at the meeting that today leprosy
patients can be cured through multidrug therapy and they can live
a normal life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
