<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Military Exchanges Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Friendly exchanges between the
armed forces of China and the United States have been increasing
along with Sino-US relations since the meeting between presidents
Jiang Zemin and Bill Clinton in Manila last November, where they
discussed principles for further growth of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
After the visit to the U.S. last December by Vice-Chairman of
China's Central Military Commission and Defense Minister Chi
Haotian, there was a marked improvement in bilateral military
links. The visit was regarded as a major step toward the
improvement and development of Sino-US military relations.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the US, Chi met with President Clinton and
Defense Secretary William Perry and the two sides noted the
importance of bilateral ties in safeguarding peace in the
Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In February, Kui Fulin, a Deputy Chief of General Staff of the
China's People's Liberation Army (PLA), visited the US, and in
July, Wu Quanxu, another Deputy Chief also visited there, as did
Fu Quanyou, Chief of the PLA General Staff, in August.
</P>
<P>
John Shalikashvili, Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff;
Archie Clemins, Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Pacific Fleet;
Dennis Reimer, the Chief of Staff of the U.S. Army; and Chief of
Naval Operations Jay Johnson visited China this year.
</P>
<P>
These high-level exchanges have increased mutual understanding,
friendship, and trust and have provided channels for the two sides
to discuss issues of common concern. The two armed forces have
made some substantial progress in regional security matters and in
bilateral ties through these exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have smoothly arranged for American warships to
anchor in Hong Kong after July 1 of this year, and 8 groups of
U.S. warships have been in Hong Kong since that time. US warships
also visited the Chinese city of Qingdao this September.
</P>
<P>
The first visit to the U.S. by a Chinese fleet last March was a
significant voyage that opened a new chapter in relations between
the two navies and showed the PLA's mighty and civilized image to
the whole world.
</P>
<P>
The two armed forces have also had exchanges in the fields of
military science, logistics and military law.
</P>
<P>
Sino-US military ties obviously constitute an important part of
overall bilateral ties, and an official from China's Defense
Ministry's Foreign Affairs Bureau says that Jiang Zemin's
forthcoming visit to the U.S. will help develop friendly ties
between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The PLA is ready to have more exchanges with its U.S.
counterparts in various fields and at various levels on the basis
of the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, and on equality, mutual
benefit, and mutual respect as part of a joint effort for peace,
security, and stability in the Asia-Pacific region and the world
as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
