<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Warns Greece, Cyprus Over Joint Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Foreign Ministry
warned today that the ongoing joint maneuvers by Greece and Cyprus
will negatively affect the Cyprus peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly press conference here, Sermet Atacanli,
spokesman for the ministry, said that the Greek-Cypriot joint
military exercises would not be conducive to finding a solution
to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Under their joint defense pact, Greek and Cypriot troops
started one-week joint exercises, code-named "Nikiforos '97," last
Friday in the Greek Cypriot-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
The exercises have drawn strong protests from both Turkey and
the Turkish Cypriots, which accused Greece and Greek Cypriots of
damaging the climate of talks on the island.
</P>
<P>
All parties concerned should avoid actions which might make an
adverse impact on the settlement of the Cyprus issue, Atacanli
said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the small island state has become worse after
the Cypriot government signed a deal early this year to buy S-300
anti-aircraft missiles from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military has threatened that it would destroy these
missiles if they are finally deployed in Cyprus, saying that the
missiles constitute a serious threat to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish navy and police have tightened their security
measures on those ships sailing through the Bosporus Strait in
order to prevent the delivery of the Russian-made missiles to
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Greece have warned Turkey not to attack Russian or
Greek ships carrying the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of an abortive pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have been making
efforts for the reunification of the divided country, but no
tangible results have been achieved so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
