<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Economic Ministers to Discuss Regional Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA, Malaysia, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The currency
problems affecting the Southeast Asia region will be discussed at
the 29th ASEAN Economic Ministers (AEM) meeting on October 16-18,
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz
said here today.
</P>
<P>
She said, "Although currency discussions might not be within
our (AEM's) jurisdiction but that of finance ministers, we should
be discussing it."
</P>
<P>
This was "because currency issues are related to trade and
investments... We must look at the linkages," she told reporters
while checking out media facilities at the media center at the
Sunway Lagoon Resort Hotel where the AEM will be held.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe it would lead towards ASEAN's full management (of the
problem)," she said, adding that before this, there had been no
informal talks on the issue by ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members -- Thailand, Indonesia, the Philippines,
Indonesia and Malaysia -- have borne the brunt of severe currency
speculation since July with their currencies falling between 25-30
percent against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, in the past few days, some currencies recouped part of
their losses. Malaysia's ringgit came back from a low of 3.41 just
two weeks ago to the 3.04 level last week.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said, "Malaysia is expected to present a background
paper on the issue at the Senior Economic Officials Meeting (SEOM)
either today or tomorrow," and that the paper would include the
impact the crisis had on affected countries.
</P>
<P>
To a question whether the economic ministers would discuss the
setting up of an ASEAN fund to help countries deal with currency
problems, she said, "If such a fund was being proposed, it would
be discussed by ASEAN finance ministers."
</P>
<P>
What economic ministers want to do is to "start a dialogue on
this... come to a meeting of minds and to coordinate our
approaches," she said, adding "I cannot say what will come out of
this but it would be a free-wheeling discussion."
</P>
<P>
She is of the view that the discussions on the regional
currency problems at the AEM proposed by Malaysia could provide
valuable input in dealing with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
She said ASEAN's experience in handling the crisis could
complement the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank's
efforts to look into ways to curb excessive speculation and
manipulation in the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
Both multilateral agencies have charged Malaysia with
initiating studies into ways to curb currency manipulation, with
the latter consistently calling for greater transparency in
foreign exchange trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
