<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Slide on Lackluster Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed down today on lackluster trading, with continuing selling
of industrials to finance the Telstra (telecommunications giant)
offering and fears surrounding the 10th anniversary of the stock
market crash.
</P>
<P>
"The market was sluggish," said broker Peter Struk of Reynolds
and Co. "It drifted virtually most of the day. People are still
selling industrials to get into Telstra."
</P>
<P>
He said some investors had talked about the anniversary of the
October 20, 1987, the Black Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index was down 31.2 points at 2663.3 after
an intra-day high of 2694.5 and a low of 2662.1.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 241.94 million trades valued at 679.05
million Australian dollars (499.1 million U.S. dollars), and falls
of 750 easily outnumbered rises of 387.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 11.4 points at 1319.5 and the
all industrials index was down 56 points at 4372.1.
</P>
<P>
Among the resources giants, blue chip BHP dropped 28 cents, WMC
fell 11 and Rio Tinto was down 19.2 cents.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Coca-Cola Amatil continued to lose ground today
because of ongoing Southeast Asian currency turmoil and its
exposure in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The bank sector continued to lose ground as speculation on
another interest rate reduction dampened, with some investors now
suggesting it might not occur until next year, if at all, brokers
said.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 2.8 points at 1327.9, boosted in early
trading by a higher gold bullion price. Sydney trading in gold
bullion closed at 329.35 U.S. dollars an ounce after opening at
330.15.  
</P>
</TEXT>
