<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Proved Oil Reserves to Trend Down Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The world's net proved oil
reserves will most probably begin to decrease during the second
quarter of the 21st century, a group of leading international
experts said here today.
</P>
<P>
By that time, the addition of commercial oil reserves will not
be able to compensate oil production, according to a review and
forecast paper delivered by the Russian experts at the ongoing
15th World Petroleum Congress.
</P>
<P>
But the amount of remaining unexplored world oil resources will
allow to provide an addition of proved reserves due to new
discoveries in the first quarter of next century, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, successful addition of gas reserves due to new
discoveries will continue beyond the middle of the new century,
according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that at present, the basic trends in petroleum
exploration indicate a decline in scales of new discoveries in
long-term explored basins and a complication of newly discovered
accumulation types in old basins.
</P>
<P>
The share of gas discoveries in total world energy discoveries
has been increasing while that of oil has been decreasing, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The conditions for oil exploration will continue to be more
complicated because of a decrease in new discoveries and
complications in the nature of new accumulations in old basins,
they said, adding that another factor complicating exploration in
the next century will be an increase in drilling depths.
</P>
<P>
So far, most of the assessments of the world's recoverable oil
reserves have fallen between 300 to 400 billion tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
