<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Up 77.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
in August increased 77.7 percent from a year earlier to 817.8
billion yen (6.8 billion U.S. dollars), the Finance Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise to the yen's weakness against
the dollar, which gave export competitiveness to Japanese goods,
and to a strong demand in overseas markets such as the United
States against weak demand in Japan.
</P>
<P>
In goods and services trading in August, Japan registered a
surplus of 326.6 billion yen (2.7 billion U.S. dollars), about 65
times more than that of last year, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus in merchandise trade in August expanded 68.0
percent to 912.6 billion yen (7.6 billion U.S. dollars), up for
the fifth straight month, following a 50.5 percent surge in the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 13.8 percent to 3,826.5 billion yen (31.9 billion
dollars), while imports edged up 3.4 percent to 2,913.8 billion yen
(24.3 billion U.S. dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In service trade, including tourism, Japan posted a deficit of
586.0 billion yen (4.9 billion U.S. dollars), up from a deficit of
538.2 billion yen (4.5 billion U.S. dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the August data, Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo
Muraoka said the recent sharp growth in Japan's current account
surplus will end before too long.
</P>
<P>
"We believe it (the sharp rise) will be mended sooner or
later," the top government spokesman told a press conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
