<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successful in Increasing Onshore Oil Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- After 30-odd years of
scientific research and practice, China has scored remarkable
progress in increasing crude oil recovery by developing the oil
polymer-driven technology.
</P>
<P>
According to Han Dakuang, a senior expert at the China National
Petroleum Corp (CNPC), most of the country's oilfields belong to
the continental deposits as far as reserve layers are concerned,
with oil wells containing more water.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC), the
expert noted that about two thirds of the country's crude reserves
remained to be extracted. And it has become a pressing task to
develop oil recovery technology.
</P>
<P>
Han said that as early as in the 1960s, China started interior
experiments on the polymer-driven technology and achieved
positive results in Xinjiang and Daqing, the country's largest
oilfield.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, China has made six pilot experiments in the
oilfields of Daqing, Dagang and Henan, resulting in the decline of
the water content and higher crude output in these oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Starting in the 1990s, the country expanded the experiments
into industrial production, with more satisfactory results.
</P>
<P>
The expert said that the polymer-driven technology is very
promising and more mature in terms of technological application,
which produced higher economic returns after being applied to
the country's various major oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Experiments show that injection of one ton of polymer into the
oil wells will turn out an additional 167 tons of crude.
</P>
<P>
To provide more polymer for the oilfields, the country has set
up the world's largest polymer-making plant with an annual
production capacity of more than 50,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The expert expected the country to pump out an additional 5 to
7 million tons of crude annually by the year 2000 by spreading the
use of the new technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
