<HEADLINE> Hungarian PM Optimistic Over Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Horn
Gyula has said that the country's economy and its people's living
standards will improve considerably in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Nepszava newspaper reported today that Horn made the
remarks at a mass rally in the capital yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the policies of his government had
started to pay off, and he would not allow any deviation from this
road of development.
</P>
<P>
Horn also called on opposition parties to cooperate with the
government. He said that with 72 percent of votes in the National
Assembly, he was confident his coalition government would stay to
the end of its term.
</P>
<P>
The present Hungarian government is a coalition between the
Hungarian Socialist Party (HSP) and the Alliance of Free
Democrats(AFD).
</P>
<P>
Horn has also promised to reduce the minimum age for
entitlement to free public transportation from 70 to 65. 
</P>
