<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments in Indonesia Approach 73 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Investments implemented in
Indonesia, under both foreign and domestic investment schemes, in
the 6th Five-year Development Plan (1994-1999) have reached 72.89
billion U.S. dollars, 97.43 percent of the 74.9 billion dollar
target.
</P>
<P>
But to ensure full achievement of the investment target,
services for investors must be improved, Iskandar, vice chairman
for development and implementation supervision of the Capital
Investment Coordinating Agency (BKPK), said Sunday in Mataram,
West Nusa Tenggara, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
From April 1994 to September 1997, the total number of approved
local investment projects reached 2,763 worth 99.53 billion
dollars, while foreign investment projects reached 2,700 worth
118.4 billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There have been efforts underway to spread investment
throughout the country, particularly outside Java in eastern
Indonesia. This has shown some improvement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iskandar said the reason that not all domestic and foreign
projects approved had been implemented was because prospective
investors still faced some constraints.
</P>
<P>
He said the problems included the necessary funding support,
difficulty in raw material supply and finding skilled and trained
workers and the long process of permit issuance in the provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
