<HEADLINE> World Mark Hightlights Swimming Compeition at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yan of Liaoning province
broke the 400-meter women's individual medley world record while
Olympic champion Le Jingyi swam the year best on the opening day
of the China's Eighth Naitonal Games here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chen, 16, captured the gold medal by clocking four minutes and
34.79 seconds, beating the previous world mark of 4:36.10 set by
Petra Schneider of former East Germany on August 1, 1982.
</P>
<P>
Le, winner of the 100-meter freestyle in the Atlanta Games last
year, captured the first swimming gold of the National Games in
her discipline with the year-best 54.10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who had a poor show in Atlanta, stole the limelight from
the two-time Olympian and world 50-meter freestyle record holder
Le, signalling the advent of the Chinese younger swimmers who are
to take over the torch from the veterans.
</P>
<P>
"She was chased very hard by second-placer Wu Yanyan of Guangxi
Autunomous Region," Chen's coach Han Bingyan said. "She had to
strike out for the gold, which probably was the factor for her
record."
</P>
<P>
Wu, also a teenager who competed in the Atlanta Games, finished
second with 4:36.28, followed by Ning Bo of Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
"I had not expected to set a new world mark," said Chen. "But I
have trained hard after I returned home from Atlanta."
</P>
<P>
"I'm very satisfied with the results," Le said. "After all, I
resumed systematic training only months ago after the Pan-Pacific
Championships early this year."
</P>
<P>
Le was followed by teenager Shan Ying of the Chinese Army and
Sun Guiling of Guangdong province, who were timed at 54.49 and
55.33 seconds respetively.
</P>
<P>
Being the best short-course women swimmer in the world, as her
coach Zhou Ming said, Le was very elated to see the new swimmers
have getting more mature.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely congratulate Chen Yan on her world mark," Le said.
"I hope the young swimmers will have better performances in the
international competitions."
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100-meter breaststroke, Guangdong's Zeng Qiliang,
who finished seventh in the Atlanta Games, won the gold with a
Asian-mark of one minute and 1.66 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Local swimmer Chen Jianhong finished second with 1:02.29 and
Chinese Army's Zhu Yi at third with 1:02.61.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200-meter freestyle gold was taken by Shanghai's Chen
Zhou, who was followed by Tianjin's Du Jie and Hebei's Deng
Qingsong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
