<HEADLINE> NAA Stresses Transatlantic Ties in Wider Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The annual session of the
North Atlantic Assembly (NAA), which ended here today, agreed that
a new dimension should be added to the Euro-Atlantic alliance to
manage new threats to peace and freedom.
</P>
<P>
The threats were defined as nationalistic, ethnic, religious,
socio-economic and ecological crises and conflicts.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the new threats, NAA President William Roth
appealed to delegates to shoulder the responsibility of
burden-sharing enlargement costs, to seriously consider new
missions for the transatlantic alliance and to expedite the
internal and external adaptation of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Roth said the three tasks need both transatlantic consensus and
improved military capability.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from NATO member states and other European countries
maintained that transatlantic interests should not be undermined
by divergence of views and differences among alliance members.
</P>
<P>
Adverse debates are expected in the following months when the
parliaments of NATO member states start ratifying the accession of
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
"As parliamentarians, we must ensure that the ratification of
the first new members of the alliance is shepherded through our
respective nations expeditiously and decisively," Roth said.
</P>
<P>
Enlargement had to be accompanied by a collective determination
to streamline, restructure and modernize the defense capabilities
that in turn rendered NATO members into a constructive and
indispensable bedrock of Euro-Atlantic security, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's Secretary-General, Javier Solana, said the
expansion of the military alliance will not be limited by
geography.
</P>
<P>
Future enlargement will be defined by common values, he added.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said NATO's opening was not just a gesture but
rather a guarantee for future security and stability.
</P>
<P>
NAA delegates were aware that only as close partners would the
transatlantic alliance succeed in meeting global challenges.
</P>
<P>
Partners of the transatlantic alliance were urged to lay the
foundation for a successful global partnership through joint
movement toward multilateral cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
