<HEADLINE> Population Studies Make Fast Progress in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Population studies in China has
made fast progress since the mid-1970s, and more than 50 research
and education institutions of a fairly large scale have been
set up across the country.
</P>
<P>
Noted Chinese population scientists told a press conference
here today that many of these institutions have established
exchanges and cooperative ties with organizations overseas such as
the United Nations Population Fund, the World Health Organization
(WHO) and some other prestigious institutions.
</P>
<P>
The China Population Association (CPA), founded in 1981, is the
country's leading academic organization in the field of population
studies, said Li Honggui, vice-chairman of the China Organizing
Committee of the ongoing 23rd IUSSP (International Union for the
Scientific Study of Population) General Population Conference and
executive vice-president of the society.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the CPA has 29 branches across China, and 11
committees specialized in population and economy, population and
society, population survey, quality of population, population
policies, population and ecology, ethnic population, population
and the market, the female population, and population periodicals.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the CPA sponsors a national population conference
every four years, as well as annual forums on specific topics, Li
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
