<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Shellings Send S. Leoneans Fleeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite a lull in the clash
over the weekend between Nigerian soldiers of ECOMOG and Sierra
Leonean troops at Jui, 13 miles east of the capital, hundreds of
people today continued to flee from nearby Wellington village.
</P>
<P>
A family of five died when stray shells fired by Nigerian
gunners hit their residence on Saturday. Over 200 people are in
hospital suffering from fragment wounds, a medical officer said.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning in Wellington, this reporter saw mothers
with babies strapped on their backs, the aged and other sweating
displaced people walking long distances barefooted.
</P>
<P>
One eyewitness told Xinhua, "I just left my house without
deciding where I am heading for."
</P>
<P>
The Jui area remains closed and stern looking Sierra Leonean
soldiers backed by the people's army set up checkpoints with huge
boulders, scrapped cars and worn out tyres on the road leading to
the Nigerian base.
</P>
<P>
"No one goes through," a soldier shouted to this reporter as
he crawled behind a sub machine gun.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources said it is still not known whether the
Sierra Leonean troops have routed the Nigerians from their Jui
base as was claimed by government spokesman Allieu Kamara. But
parading soldiers in the capital seemed to be in high spirit
since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have captured many Nigerian soldiers and this time we
shall not just let them go like the last time," said a military
officer.
</P>
<P>
Observers attributed the reference to the surrender of some
300 Nigerian soldiers on June 2 when rebels captured the
Nigerians at a seaside hotel in the west of the capital. They
were freed unarmed a few days later.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government Torchlight newspaper said today, "More than
100 Nigerians including six top officers were captured from Jui,
Kenema in the east and Gondama in the southern Bo." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
