<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Promises Wider Alliance in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 13 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Secretary General Javier Solana said today the
expansion of the military alliance would not be limited simply by
geography.
</P>
<P>
At a plenary session of the North Atlantic Assembly (NAA),
Solana said that enlargement would be defined by common values,
not merely by geographical division.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO's expansion membership would include all
those qualified, including Russia, if it intended to apply for
entry into the NATO.
</P>
<P>
"Time is moving so fast that it is hard to make any
prediction," said Solana who arrived here today to address the
plenary session of the four-day meeting which closed today.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO's expansion is a guarantee for future security and
stability rather than a gesture.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the entry of Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic into the NATO would be the joint responsibilities of all
the participants at the NAA annual session in building a new
alliance.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the cost of enlargement "will be manageable
and will be shared fairly by the 19 NATO members".
</P>
<P>
He argued that the enlargement benefits far outweigh the cost
of enlargement, and "the cost of not opening will be much more
expensive."
</P>
<P>
Solana said enlargement costs would be an important decision
with a political dimension, which "will benefit the generations to
come."
</P>
<P>
All members of the NATO Partnership for Peace program will be
involved in future planning and decision making of NATO, Solana
also said.
</P>
<P>
The NAA session was attended by about 300 parliamentarians from
the 16 NATO member states and 15 central and eastern European
countries, Albania, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Macedonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania,
Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Solana said it was important for the meeting to be held here as
it showed Romania, the first non-NATO member hosting the NAA
meeting, had gone far and fast in NATO integration.
</P>
<P>
However, Solana did not reveal whether Romania would be
included in the second wave of the enlargement in early 1999. He
said the Madrid summit was only the beginning of the expansion
process instead of the end of it.
</P>
<P>
Romania has not been invited to the Madrid summit to join the
accession negotiations mainly because of its delay in economic
restructuring and minority problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
