<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets With WPC Participants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, in a
meeting with participants from 90 countries and regions to the
on-going 15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC) here today, said that
it is an occassion for Chinese petroleum sector to increase its
co-operative relations with foreign counterparts on the basis on
equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Li said he believes that participants can increase mutual
understanding through discussions and exchanges and promote the
development and technical advancement of the oil industry globally.
</P>
<P>
Li discussed the development of China's petroleum industry and
said the Chinese government has always paid close attention to its
development and has designated the industry one of the key
economic sectors in the national development program, and the
industry has a pivotal role in China's economic growth in the last
five years of the century.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China's petroleum industry has had some great
achievements over the past 40 years and domestic oil products have
not only basically satisfied the rising domestic demand, but also
are exported.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China's rapid economic growth will create more
demand for oil, natural gas, and related products in the future,
but by "stablizing the east and developing the west" the oil
industry in China will develop sustainably.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country with more than 1.2 billion people, he
noted, China's hydrocarbon resources still can not meet the
fast-growing demand and oil resources need further exploration and
development, but "it takes time to build new oilfields."
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem, he said, the Chinese government has
formulated a policy of developing both domestic and overseas
markets with various forms of international co-operation, such as
trade or investment on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that some multinationals in recent years have
been optimistic about the China market and have discussed
cooperation with Chinese counterparts, and the Chinese government
welcomes and supports these actions.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Dirk van der Meer, the WPC president, said on behalf of all
the participants in the meeting that he would like to extend his
gratitude for the work done by the Chinese
organizers. Participants have used the opportunity to improve
their understanding of China's moderization drive, he said.
</P>
