<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Criminal Tribunal Dogged by Staffing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda continues to be dogged by a shortage of
competent prosecutors to lead the on-going trials of the 1994
genocide suspects, the East African newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Recruitment of competent staff in both the Tribunals is my
biggest problem," Judge Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor of
the International Criminal Tribunals for Rwanda and Yugoslavia,
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of vacancies but I have always been looking
for people with two languages so as to avoid problems, but to be
honest with you it has been very difficult for me to get the
right people", he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that most people with the desired qualifications have
been reluctant to join the Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The use of non-professionals to translate from Kinyarwanda to
English has sometimes caused misunderstandings in the tribunal,
said the press report.
</P>
<P>
In a recent case, a witness under cross examination called a
defence counsel, named Tiphaine Dickson, a liar on the basis of a
misunderstanding caused by a translator and complained to
Tribunal President Laity Kama.
</P>
<P>
Kama then apologized to Dickson and warned the translator not
to give her own opinion but to accurately convey what the witness
had said.
</P>
<P>
This was not the first time the president of the tribunal has
had to warn prosecution officers to be better prepared and more
accurate during sessions, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
