<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Trade Deficit Shrinks Remarkably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel's trade deficit
shrank 25 percent to 6 billion US dollars during the first
three-quarters of the year, in comparison to the same period in
1996, Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics announced today.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that imports in the first nine months totaled
21.45 billion dollars, while exports reached 15.36 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli economists are concerned that the reduced deficit
is not the result of an increase in exports, but rather the
economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
On the positive front, economist Ruth Lowenstein, of economic
planning company Sadan Lowenstein Limited, pointed out that there
has been an increase in investment goods being brought into the
country within the figures for imports.
</P>
<P>
Lowenstein said that "This is good as it shows an improvement
in the overall composition of imports."
</P>
<P>
But he added that it is too early to say this is the end of
the downward cycle in the economy, that is likely to continue for
a while yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
