<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta to Hold ECOWAS Citizens Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG) has alerted that the military junta in Sierra
Leone plans to arrest, detain and hold hostage as many west
African citizens as it can capture.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the junta is to hold the hostages as human shield
and use them to bargain in future negotiations with sub-regional
leaders for the return of Foday Sankoh, the rebel leader now
detained in Nigeria, according to an ECOMOG statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued on Sunday by ECOMOG headquarters in
Liberia, said the junta also attacked ECOMOG protected areas last
Thursday and Sunday, and the force had no option but to defend
itself.
</P>
<P>
"Attacking ECOMOG protected areas would only aggravate the
crisis and bring more hardship on civilians who are already
traumatized by the recklessness and state of anarchy the junta
has unleashed on the citizens since May," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Many citizens of othe west African countries and Sierra
Leoneans are currently taking refuge in ECOMOG protected areas
which the junta plans to attack to capture civilians and
soldiers, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the junta claimed at the weekend that it had overrun
a Nigerian military base outside the capital Freetown and
captured some Nigerian soldiers, who constitute the bulk of
ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
Describing the claim as "wishful thinking", ECOMOG said the
junta were telling lies.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu was reported
as saying Sunday night that his troops were still holding the
position allegedly overrun by the junta.
</P>
<P>
West African countries decided on Saturday to resume dialogue
with the junta toward peaceful settlement of the crisis in Sierra
Leone triggered off by the the May 25 coup that toppled the
legitimate government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
So far there has been no response from the junta.  
</P>
</TEXT>
