<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Plants, Pests Invade Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- At least ten kinds of foreign
pests invaded Uganda due to flouting quarantine, The New Vision
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The large amount of water hyacinth is suffocating almost all
other water organisms in some waters, and latana camara in its
full developed stature of five meters high are stifling all other
plants beneath them in shallow ponds and wetlands.
</P>
<P>
Both water hyacinth and latana camara, or "the curse of India"
as referred to by locals, were declared by Ugandan authorities as
the forbidden plants to import. But still, they have been
introduced into the country in earlier sixties and
fifties.
</P>
<P>
The recent case is a micro-organism called Em 4 which local
scientists said is suspected to cause diseases both to plants and
animals and to have negative environmental effect. Em 4 is
imported by some farmers visiting Indonesia in July. The
substance of Em 4 was impounded in August when the presidential
office intervened. The garden using the substance now is under
scientific observation.
</P>
<P>
Em 4 was brought into the country in a luggage and not
declared to custom, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Other dangerous imported plants and pests include dodder weeds
and oxalis from Kenya which choke crops, coffee wilt from Zaire,
cassava mite from south America and cotris woolly white fly.
</P>
<P>
Officials here said that evading pre-export plant inspection
also caused a big loss to Ugandan exporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Begin Water Treatment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Work on a water treatment plant
for improving water supply in Bangladesh's capital Dhaka will
begin on October 21, said sources from the city authorities today.
</P>
<P>
The building up of the water treatment plant at Saidabad is
aimed at increasing the water supply by an additional 225 million
liters or 50 million gallons daily.
</P>
<P>
The plant to be financed jointly by the World Bank and the
French government will cost an estimated 7.5 billion taka (about
168.91 million U.S. dollars), and the work is expected to complete
by the year 2002, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
For Dhaka, a city with a population of 9 million, the present
water consumption has been estimated at 1.3 billion liters per
day, but the quantity of supply through 224 deep tubewells and
water supply works stands at 850 million liters, leaving a daily
shortfall of 450 million liters, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken up this plan apprehending that
extraction of water from underground through deep tubewells might
cause an adverse effect to high-rise buildings, the sources said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
