<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Belgian Defense Ministers Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Defense Minister
Jean-Paul Ponsle's current China visit will not only increase
friendship and cooperation between the two armed forces, but
also make new contributions to Sino-Belgian relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese National Defense Minister Chi Haotian made this remark
today in talks with his Belgian counterpart Ponsle, who is
here on an official goodwill visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and
state councillor, extended welcome to Ponsle, who is the first
Belgian defense minister to visit China since the establishment of
diplomatic relations between the two countries in 1971.
</P>
<P>
He said that since then, the two countries have had fruitful
cooperation in political, economic and military areas.
</P>
<P>
China places great emphasis on advancing friendly and
cooperative ties with Belgium, he said, adding that it is ready to
promote bilateral relations on the basis of mutual respect, and
seeking common grounds while reserving differences.
</P>
<P>
he said, "The Chinese People's Liberation Army is ready to
redouble its efforts to further relations between the two armed
forces."
</P>
<P>
On peace-keeping actions of the United Nations (UN), Chi said
that as a permanent member of the UN Security Council, China
supports the UN in maintaining world peace and security in
accordance with its Charter, and that China adheres to principles,
upholds justice, safeguards the rights and interests of developing
nations and has participated in the UN peace-keeping actions in
a constructive and responsible manner.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Ponsle on China's guilding principle concerning
the UN peace-keeping actions, reform and opening-up, the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China, China's
defense-oriented national policy and its independent foreign
policy of peace.
</P>
<P>
Ponsle said that as China is a permanent member of the UN
Security Council, Belgium is willing to exchange views with China
on security issues. He also briefed Chi on Belgium's participation
in peace-keeping actions in Croatia, the reform of the Belgian
armed forces and Belgium's views on European security.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Belgian-Chinese relations have been developing
smoothly, and that leaders of the two armed forces have frequently
exchanged visits in recent years, thus increasing contacts between
the two armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
