<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Downplays Israeli Military Chief's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today downplayed the
visit by Israeli Chief of Staff Amnon Shahak -- a focus of
attention for Arab countries -- as a regular one.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press briefing here, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Shahak's visit is aimed at
exchanging views with high-ranking Turkish military officials over
some issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
He declined to elaborate on the topics to be discussed by
Shahak and his Turkish counterpart Ismail Hakki Karadayi.
</P>
<P>
Describing the visit as "regular and routine," Atacanli added
that the Israeli military chief's tour was a return visit for the
one to Israel by Karadayi last February.
</P>
<P>
Shahak arrived here yesterday on a three-day visit to Turkey
aimed at enhancing bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two top officers are expected to discuss the scheduled
joint naval exercises of Israel, Turkey and the United States
and Israel's involvement in the project to modernized Turkey's
tank units.
</P>
<P>
On the three-way naval war games, Atacanli said that it might
be held in mid-November, but added that the final date would be
announced by the Turkish General Staff.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side had earlier asked for the further postponement of
the Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint maneuvers, re-scheduled to start on
November 16. Some reports put the date in next January.
</P>
<P>
However, neither Israel nor Turkey had given any positive
response to the U.S. suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's involvement in the joint exercises has been strongly
criticized by some Arab countries, which accused Ankara of
betraying the interests of the Muslim world by developing closer
military ties with the Jewish rival.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government had repeatedly stated that its
cooperation with Israel is not directed against any other
countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Shahak is reportedly to persuade the Turkish
military to replace its tank units with Israeli-made Merkava 3
tanks, which are one of the world's most advanced types.
</P>
<P>
Turkish-Israeli cooperation in military and defense fields has
gained a rapid expansion since early last year, when the two
countries signed two agreements to allow joint warplane exercise
in each other's airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
