<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Become More Open, Prosperous: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Wang Zhongyu, minister of
China's State Economic and Trade Commission, said here today that
China is expected to become a more open and prosperous country and
an important participant in the world economy in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the Sixth East Asia Economic
Summit in the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, Wang
briefed some 1,000 delegates from over 50 countries on the
economic growth in China and reform of its state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He described the ongoing three-day summit organized by the
World Economic Forum as the most important meeting held in the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region following the World
Bank/International Monetary Fund annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy will grow at an annual rate of 8 percent in
 the remaining years of the century, while the country's annual
inflation rate will be kept below 5 percent, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
China could maintain a 7 percent growth rate in the first 10
years of the next century, he said, predicting that "a more open
and prosperous China will become an important participant in the
world economy, particularly in the East Asian economy, and a
cooperation partner to be trusted."
</P>
<P>
China has made great progress in its economic development since
1979, under the policy of reform and opening to the outside world
initiated by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, Wang said,
adding that its annual growth rate of gross domestic product (GDP)
reached 12.1 percent during the 1991-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the growth rate of the Chinese
economy was 9.7 percent and the price increases were lowered to
6.1 percent, he said, noting that the Chinese economy had
embarked on a track of continuous, rapid and sound development.
</P>
<P>
As to the restructuring of the state-run enterprises, Wang said
the Chinese government is ready to bail out most of the
loss-making large- and medium-sized state-run enterprises within
the coming three years.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the state-run enterprises provides a great
opportunity for foreign investors, Wang stressed, calling on the
foreign industrial and commercial community to take part in the
reform and reorganization of China's state-run enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
