<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tanker Market Expected to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- World tanker market is likely
to improve in the next two or three years though it is facing
strong competition from pipeline transportation, experts attending
the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
There are signs that some of the positive development for tanker
demand seen in the early 1990s will be restored by the end of the
century, Jon Edvard Sundnes with Norway's First Olsen Tankers Ltd
said at a forum of the congress.
</P>
<P>
The world tanker market experienced a major setback in 1994 after
a significant increase in tanker demand in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Sundnes said that while the development in oil consumption in the
United States and Europe were earlier regarded as the driving force
behind tanker demand, Far East Asia's importance has been increasing.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Far East oil consumption is expected to
continue its growth and crude oil import will increase as more
refineries come on stream in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is now assumed that the increased demand for transport to the
Far East will more than compensate for the lost transport demand to
the Atlantic Basin," Sundnes noted.
</P>
<P>
Much of the transport demand for tankers over the coming years
is expected to be for short haul trading, and many new oilfield
developments will be offshore, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the back of this development a market for shuttle tankers at
the offshore oilfields will develop further in competition with
pipelines, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, the tanker market is volatile, and even
though the most probable scenario points to a broad based
recovery, there is still a downside risk in the market.
</P>
<P>
The main threat to recovery is the fragility of the recovery in
the OECD region and the present new building potential due to
increased yard capacity, Sundnes said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
