<HEADLINE> Sixth East Asia Economic Summit Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Economic Forum's
Sixth East Asia Economic Summit opened here today to discuss the
economic development in China, the economic growth in East Asia as
a whole and possible Asia-Europe-America triangular economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day meeting at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, Klaus Schwab, president and founder of the
26-year-old forum, said the meeting with the participation of
about 1,000 delegates from more than 50 countries is significant
for the global economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, minister of China's State Economic and Trade
Commission, said in a keynote address at the opening session that
China will maintain the 8-percent growth rate of its economy
annually in the remaining years of this century while keeping its
inflation rate under 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a more opening and prosperous China could
become an important participant of the world economy, particularly
the East Asian economy, and a cooperation partner to be trusted in
the coming years.
</P>
<P>
According to the agenda of the meeting, a plenary session will
be held later today specially to discuss how to further China's
integration into the world economy. Prior to the session, two
other sessions are expected to be held in parallel focusing on
"Chongqing, a new region opening for the 21st century" and "Hainan
entering a new century."
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region will host a reception and an official
opening dinner tonight for the participants of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos and Singapore Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong are expected to address the meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
