<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up Three More Urea Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government will
set up three more urea fertilizer factories to meet the growing
demand for urea and phosphate fertilizer in the country, the
independent United News of Bangladesh (UNB) reported today.
</P>
<P>
This statement was made by Commerce and Industry Minister
Tofael Ahmed while addressing a gathering in the country's second
largest city of Chittagong Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh has six urea fertilizer factories which
produce about 2.1 million tons of urea against the local demand
for 2.5 million tons a year, the UNB said.
Natural gas is the only raw material used in producing urea in
Bangladesh, the UNB said.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the minister also talked about the government's
disinvestment plan for loss-making state-owned enterprises (SOEs).
He said the government would follow a realistic approach in
disinvesting SOEs, considering the grievances of laborers and
workers, the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, in the twin process of globalization and
liberalization, Bangladesh has to go for disinvestment of the
SOEs, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Due to misrule, mismanagement, corruption and nepotism, the
profitable SOEs of the early 1970s had now become loss-making
enterprises, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that a government can not survive for long by
incurring annual loss of 25 billion taka (about 563.10 million
U.S. dollars) from the SOEs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
