<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Tighten Border Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has decided to tighten border control to prevent
illegal immigrants and smugglers, The Star newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that 17 billion Rand, or 3.6 billion
U.S. dollars, is being lost in revenue every year, and 500 people
are entering South Africa illegally every month, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
As a major step, the cabinet has approved a plan to restrict
the number of international airports to 10.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Department deputy director-general, Bernie
Fanaroff, said the measure will bring South Africa in line with
international practice.
</P>
<P>
He said cross-border flights are currently allowed to land at
virtually all airports.
</P>
<P>
The 10 airports to be allowed to clear goods and people for or
from international flights are Johannesburg, Cape Town, Durban,
Bloemfontein international airports, and airports of Lanseria,
Nelspruit, Upington, Pietersburg, Mmabatho and Port Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
A deadline has been suggested in April 1998, when all
facilities would have to be granted international status, the
paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
