<HEADLINE> Drifting Oil Tanker off Scottish Coast Towed to Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A 10,000-ton oil tanker
drifting off the coast of northern Scotland was saved today from
the teeth of a howling gale and towed to safety after an overnight
rescue operation by British coastguards, media reports here said.
</P>
<P>
The Maltese-registered Yusup K lost power Sunday night,
steering in stormy seas five miles (eight kilometers) from Holborn
Head near the Scottish coastal town of Thurso.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that three non-essential members of the
26-strong crew were airlifted to safety by a British Royal Air
Force helicopter.
</P>
<P>
The oil tanker was carrying a cargo of 9,500 tons of naphtha
from England's west coast to Teesport on the east coast.
</P>
<P>
The coastguards said that the ship was finally towed to safety
about four hours after the breakdown and would be repaired soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
