<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Refugee Emergencies are Declining, Says UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of persons of concern
to the United Nations Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) at the
begining of 1997 was 22.7 million, a decrease of 1.3 million from
that of early 1996, head of the UNHCR office Sadako Ogata said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, we are entering a period of declining refugee
emergencies and we can focus our efforts on solving some long-time
refugee situations, mainly through repatriation," Ogata said in her
opening speech at the 48th annual meeting of UNHCR's executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee, of which 53 governments are members, will oversee
UNHCR's budgets and advise on refugee protection during the meeting on
October 13-17. The central theme of this meeting is the
"challenge of refugee repatriation."
</P>
<P>
Ogata called on governments to respect humanitarian principles.
</P>
<P>
If states had "fulfilled their responsibilities as stipulated
by the committee and supported UNHCR's actions more firmly
and decisively, some of the problems we encountered could have
been avoided, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The rights of refugees, asylum and non-refoulement, are the
foundation of my mandate and I wish to reaffirm our non-negotiable
commitment to defend and promote them," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that repatriation involves more than just logistics
and it can be durable and sustainable only if refugees' rights,
including basic human rights, and justice are restored.
</P>
<P>
She believed that the situation in Bosnia exemplifies the
variety of reintegration challenges.
</P>
<P>
Physical safety must be assured, including the removal of land
mines, the result of elections must be accepted, and those who
committed crimes against humanity must be brought to justice, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Unless UNHCR's work is "part of an integrated strategy for
rehabilitation and reconciliation", she said, "its impact is
likely to be insufficient." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gas Demand Forecast to Grow 2.7 Percent Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- World gas demand is expected to
grow at an annual rate of 2.7 percent in the 15 years to 2010,
experts predicted at the 15th World Petroleum Congress here today.
</P>
<P>
Total demand for natural gas will climb to a little over 3,000
billion cubic meters in 2010 from around 2,100 billion cubic
meters in 1995, Ian Rushby, general manager in charge of gas
business of British Petroleum's Exploration Operating Company,
told a forum of the congress.
</P>
<P>
In particular, gas demand in the Asia-Pacific region is
expected to grow from around 200 billion cubic meters in 1995 to
around 470 billion cubic meters in 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
The region's growth rate of gas demand during the period will
be almost six percent annually, well ahead of the world average,
Rushby said.
</P>
<P>
"This rapid growth in the use of gas has been driven by several
factors, some related to the specific characteristics of gas
itself and others to developments in the wider energy economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In a decade during which environmental protection has risen to
the top of the political agenda, the inherent cleanliness of gas
has been one of the key drivers of demand, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted, it is also an extremely convenient and
efficient form of fuel.
</P>
<P>
"I am firmly convinced that the fundamental drivers of future
energy demand are particularly favourable for gas," Rushby said,
noting that the factors which have led to its becoming the fuel of
choice in most energy markets worldwide will continue to drive the
growth in gas demand.
</P>
<P>
The growing trend towards liberalisation and deregulation,
particularly in the more developed energy markets, and economic
restructuring will add further stimulus to gas demand, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project to Be World Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 13 (Xinhua) --The Three Gorges project under
construction on the Yangtze River is being touted as a world
leader in many major areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Jiazhu, deputy general manager of the Yangtze
River Three Gorges Project Development Corp., the Three Gorges
flood-control project will be the most efficient in the world when
finished in 2009.
</P>
<P>
A reservoir with a storage capacity of 39.3 billion cubic
meters is designed to protect 15 million people and 1.53 million
hectares of farmland from destructive flooding on the Yangtze,
China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project also is expected to lead the world in
power generation with 26 sets of turbogenerators producing a
generating capacity of 700,000 kilowatt, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Three Gorges will generate 84.6 billion kilowatt-hours of
electricity a year, 13 billion kwh more than the Itaipu
hydroelectric station jointly operated in South America by Brazil
and Paraguay, presently the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
Wang, responsible for the design of the Three Gorges project,
said the third area of leadership will be in navigation efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Navigating the Yangtze in Sichuan province will be possible for
ships with 10,000 dwt (dead weight tonnage) between Chongqing and
Yichang of central China's Hubei province. This should reduce
shipping costs by 35 percent to 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
The size of the project is also the biggest of its kind in the
world, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Chinese researchers have spent four decades solving technical
problems that might occur in construction of the Three Gorges
Dam. A man-made canal was built for use while the main course of
the Yangtze is blocked.
</P>
<P>
A countdown has started for damming the main course of the
Yangtze from November 6-8.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
