<HEADLINE> PNA Trying to Avoid Straining Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) is trying to avoid straining ties with Jordan
despite its anger over the Israeli-Jordanian deal to release Hamas
leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Several PNA officials including Palestinian Legislative Council
(PLC) Speaker Ahmed Queria (Abu Ala) visited Amman in the last few
days to deliver the message, the Israeli English daily The
Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Queria, who met with Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali, was quoted as saying that the relations between the PNA
and Jordan was "strong."
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the media reports that the PNA was angered
by the deal between Israel and Jordan to release Yassin, the
spiritual leader of the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), and
other Palestinian prisoners. The PNA has failed to secure Yassin's
release after several attempts in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, thousands of Palestinian protesters held
demonstration in the West Bank city of Ramallah in protest against
the Israeli-Jordanian plot to bypass the PNA in releasing
Yassin.
</P>
<P>
Queria added that the PNA did not complain to Jordan about
Amman's failure to coordinate the PNA the release of Yassin and 70
other Palestinian prisoners by Israel early this month.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Jordanian King Hussein telephoned PNA leader
Yasser Arafat immediately after Yassin's release on October 1. He
noted that Arafat did not complain about Jordan's behavior to the
PLC in its emergency meeting held last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Sheikh Yassin and Hamas are speaking about Palestinian
national unity," he said. "So I hope his release will maintain
security."
</P>
<P>
Yassin, jailed by Israel for eight years, was released to
Jordan under a deal with Israel to exchange for the two Israeli
agents detained by Jordan during a botched attempt to assassinate
Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal in Amman in late September. Yassin was
later allowed to return to his home in Gaza a week ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
