<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Revenues Fall Sharply for Thai Restaurants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Many Thai restaurant operators
have reported a drop in business by as much as 50 percent in
recent months because of consumers' lower spending power,
according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
Average, middle-class families, which used to dine out once or
twice a week, now eat at home to economize.
</P>
<P>
Many of these families have members who have been made
redundant or have had their wages cut.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, fewer company executives are entertaining
their clients at upmarket restaurants to cut the company's costs.
</P>
<P>
Office workers now bring their lunch box to office, or share a
simple lunch among colleagues to save expenses.
</P>
<P>
Even at weekend dinner time, many restaurants are deserted.
</P>
<P>
S and P syndicate, a major bakery and restaurant chain with 86
outlets nationwide, expects that its sales this year would fall by
20 percent from last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
Srifah, a popular Thai restaurant chain, has seen sales fall by
more than 25 percent since the July 2 baht depreciation,
continuing a downward trend which began earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
Srifah Managing Director Taveerach Rachjaibul described the
current economic downturn as the worst in the 50 years Srifah has
been operating.
</P>
<P>
Executives of Mk Suki Japanese food chain restaurants admitted
that earnings at the chain's 70 outlets throughout the country has
so far fallen by 10 percent and are likely to fall further.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants located in hotels suffer the most, where price wars
have been launched to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants are struggling to survive, adopting various
methods, such as price freeze, discounts, give-aways, promotions
such as "buy one, get one free" and free home delivery.
</P>
<P>
Harsher cost-saving measures such as cutting year-end bonuses
and laying off staff are being considered. Mk Suki, which employs
4,000 workers, has already moved to cut utility costs, freeze new
employment, and cut advertising and promotional spending.
</P>
<P>
Reducing waste of raw materials is another way of staying
afloat.
</P>
<P>
Many restaurant operators are in dilemma whether to increase
food prices. Raising prices would mean driving away more
customers, while price freeze would mean operators will have to
bear more loss as a result of a higher value-added tax, higher
cost in raw materials and depreciated baht.
</P>
<P>
Raising prices would be the last alternative, some operators
say.
</P>
<P>
In the face of hotel restaurants' intense competition, one
hotel recently launched a promotional campaign offering two
buffets for the price of one, plus two free beers.
</P>
<P>
If things go on like this, more weak restaurants are bound to
crumble, observers believe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
