<HEADLINE> Rare Surgery on Lion Performed in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A lion trainer underwent a
successful eye operation and soon asked for another -- for his
lion, which turned out to be the world's first eye surgery on the
king beast.
</P>
<P>
The story all started two months ago when a breathtaking
beast-taming show of the Egyptian National Circus here sped
into a bloody fight between two giant lions over Gina, a new
lioness that just joined the troupe, local English-language
newspaper the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Trainer Mahassen el-Helu quickly intervened in the scene but
the lion Kota had already been slapped across the eye and could be
left blind for ever.
</P>
<P>
El-Helu canceled the performance and sought emergency medical
help to save Kota's eye.
</P>
<P>
But as very few vets in Egypt are experienced enought to
conduct an eye operation on such a large beast, she had to resort
to her own doctor Osama el-Hofi, an ophthalmologist at Cairo
University's medical college.
</P>
<P>
The doctor, who conducted a perfect eye operation on the
trainer a month ago, agreed to examine the injured lion after it
was put to sleep. He told the worried trainer that Kota still has
a chance to get back his eyesight after a sophisticated operation.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, el-Hofi conducted a cornea transplant operation
to the injured lion. The surgery, which took place at the National
Circus, one of the region's oldest and most prestigious circus, is
reported to be the first in the world.
</P>
<P>
Besides implanting the cornea of a dead cat in the lion's eye,
the doctor also conducted two other surgeries to remove cataract
from the eye, which was caused by the strong slap.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first such surgery in the world. I did it
voluntarily," said the doctor triumphantly, adding that otherwise
the lion's bad eyesight would pose a threat to the trainers during
the shows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
