<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Not Contacted to Stop Plutonium-Laden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A rocket laden with
plutonium will fly over Southern Africa today after a reported
last-ditch effort to get South African President Nelson Mandela
to block the launch failed.
</P>
<P>
The Cassini space probe, due to be launched from Cape
Canaveral in Florida of the United States at dawn, is carrying 33
kg of plutonium needed to power its seven-year journey to Venus
and Saturn.
</P>
<P>
Local mass media quoted opponents of Cassini as saying at the
weekend that the mission will cross Panama, the Caribbean,
Southern Africa and Madagascar before hurtling into space.
</P>
<P>
The opponents said the probe will pose a threat to millions of
lives because if it burns up in the atmosphere, it could cause
plutonium to rain down on the Earth, causing large number of
people to contract cancer.
</P>
<P>
They believed Mandela was "their last chance" to stop the
launch.
</P>
<P>
In a last-ditch effort to block the launch, campaigners
against the mission reportedly approached Mandela and asked him
to intervene, local daily the Sunday Independent reported
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
But presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said Mandela had
not received any request to help block the launch by yesterday
afternoon. "We don't know anything about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign affairs spokesman Pieter Swanepoel said neither had
his department received any request or contacted the American
authorities to find out what was happening with Cassini.
</P>
<P>
Both Swanepoel and Mankahlana said they did not know whether
South Africa would monitor the rocket as it crossed the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Local environmental group Earthlife said it could not comment
because it had not been aware of the mission.
</P>
<P>
Nearly seven meters in height, Cassini will be carrying 12
separate packages of scientific instruments, as well as a probe,
carrying six more bundles of sensors, which is to be dropped on
to Titan, Saturn's largest moon.
</P>
<P>
Among the instruments on Cassini are cameras to provide
pictures of Saturn, its rings and moons, and radar to pierce the
orange, hydrocarbon haze surrounding Titan.
</P>
<P>
Phil Metcalfe, spokesman for South Africa's Council for
Nuclear Safety, said yesterday that the chances of Cassini
burning up in the atmosphere were very small. Even if something
happened, South Africa had contacted with the U.S. and would
immediately speak to it about it, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
