<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Urged to Scrap Visas for Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's beleaguered tourism
industry has asked the government to waive visa requirements for
visitors staying less than a month to help rescue the industry
from an unprecedented slump caused by recent Coast violence.
</P>
<P>
Whereas some 250,000 arrivals had been expected for the peak
December-April season of the European winter, projections after
the violence were for only 125,000 visitors, local sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
Many air charters and personal bookings were canceled as some
65 Kenyans, though no tourists, have been killed in sporadic
torchings and mob attacks in the Coast Province since August 13.
</P>
<P>
The visa proposal was made by the Marketing Action Group of
the Kenya Tourist Board (KTB) which has been meeting regularly to
discuss how to pull Kenya's largest foreign exchange-earner out
of the current quagmire.
</P>
<P>
The group argued that the cumbersome visa requirement
discourages some would-be tourists and has been dropped long ago
by countries such as Thailand and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"If you don't live near an embassy or consulate offices, you
have to travel long distances or post your passport for
endorsement and most people do not like parting with their
passports," said Jim Flannery, an Irish adviser to the KTB.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kenya Association of Tour Operators (KATO) has
urged the Kenya Wildlife Service (KWS) to lower entry fees to
national parks and game reserves by 50 percent for tourists until
the crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
The entry fee currently ranges from 23 to 27 U.S. Dollars for
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
KATO also asked KWS to allow foreign travel writers, travel
agents and Kenyan journalists on familiarization tours with free
entry to parks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chairman of the Mombasa and Coast Tourist Association
Najib Balala urged the establishment of a rehabilitation fund
from which hoteliers and others could borrow on favorable terms
to rebuild their businesses after the slump.
</P>
<P>
"We are also asking the government to give a tax moratorium
for at least one year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Occupancy rates at the Coast remained between 10 and 30
percent last week, but some hotels frequented by Italians which
had been facing closure are now recording 20-40 percent occupancy
due to an aggressive media campaign in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Two Kenyan cabinet ministers, accompanied by tourism
officials, were scheduled to visit Britain, Germany, Austria,
Italy and Switzerland over a week from October 18 with the
message that Kenya is safe for visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
