<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Shanghai to Jointly Shed Lights in Sports World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Tagged as the Oriental Pearl
and Paris of the East respectively, Hong Kong and Shanghai, are
trying to combine their efforts to live up to their reputation not
only in economy, but in sports as well.
</P>
<P>
A renaissance of cooperation? Not enough.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hui-tang, born in Hong Kong and dubbed Soccer King of Asia
in the 1930s, paced a Shanghai squad to defeat an arrogant foreign
team to win the first club title for China 60 years ago, opening a
new chapter in sports exchange between Shanghai and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In an era when foreign invasion and inner unrest rocked the
country, few people noticed great feat.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong returned to China in July, people began
unveiling the sports links early this century for something
valuable.
</P>
<P>
Dated back to 1908, the soccer confederations of Hong Kong and
Shanghai inaugurated an annual inter-port duel, aiming to
establish a long-term sports exchange between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
From 1908 to 1948, except those years during two World Wars, a
total of 20 contests were played on a home-and-away format.
</P>
<P>
At that time, besides Lee, who was later elected president of
the Asian Football Confederation and vice president of FIFA, many
a Hong Kong natives left their marks in Shanghai, including
well-known stars Sun Jinshun and Liang Yutang.
</P>
<P>
The inter-port system resumed in 1987 after a 40-year absence
in a sell-out 40,000-capacity Jiangwan Stadium in Shanghai, with
the local squad winning the year's meet 3-1 last week.
</P>
<P>
The soccer contest heralded an era for the two cities to step
up exchange in sports. After Hong Kong returned to China, both
sides are eager to gear up their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Daohan, former mayor of Shanghai and current president of
Cross Straits Association, said Shanghai and Hong Kong should
cooperate like doubles partners in tennis when Shanghai is
striving to become an economic, financial, trade and information
center.
</P>
<P>
"It's like a team and we are the pair in a tennis match," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong boasts of a first division soccer league with eight
teams whereas Shanghai produces three squads for the Division A
league in the country, with Shenhua being the lone team of any
significance.
</P>
<P>
Putting aside soccer, Shanghai has produced dozens of world and
Olympic champions while Hong Kong cherished its lone Olympic gold
from surfer Lee Lai-Shan in the women's mistral in the Atlanta
Games last year.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return to the motherland provides precious
favorable conditions for our cooperation in sports," said Shanghai
vice mayor Gong Xueping.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the two sides will establish a soccer league featuring
all the top clubs on the basis of the annual inter-port soccer
tournament," he added.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has a lot to learn from Hong Kong in horse racing. "We
hope Hong Kong could give us a hand in this respect," Gong said.
</P>
<P>
Timothy Fok, head of the Hong Kong delegation for the on-going
National Games, also hoped Shanghai spare no efforts to help Hong
Kong improve its competitive sports.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange should not be limited in soccer. There are a
great potentials for us to cooperate in other events," Fok said.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu, minister of the Chinese State Physical Culture and
Sports Commission, also voiced his support for the inter-port
cooperation in sports between the two Chinese metropolitans.
</P>
<P>
"A closer tie between the two sides will surely foster the
sports development and give a boost to the whole country," Wu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
