<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Oilfield Discovered in South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A new oilfield, with an
expected daily output of some 1,000 tons of crude oil, has been
discovered in the southern part of the South China Sea, it is
learned today.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield, a basin at the mouth of the Pearl River, is 139
km from the southeastern tip of Hong Kong. the crude oil in the
field has a specific gravity of 0.79 to 0.83, according to sources
from the Nanhai East Company of the China National Offshore Oil
Corporation (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
The field is 8,500 meters from the production platform of an
oilfield at the Huizhou-26 block, which has already gone into
operation. That should provide advantageous conditions for joint
development of the two fields.
</P>
<P>
The multi-national group -- comprising the CNOOC, Italy's Agip
Overseas Corporation Ltd., the Chevron Overseas Oil Corporation
Ltd. from the United States, and the China Company of the Texaco
group of the U.S. -- discovered the oilfield when drilling
offshore earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The group has built and begun production on four oilfields in
its area of the South China Sea, yielding a combined 13,000 tons
of crude oil per day. This yield makes the area the largest
oil-field community in China.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the 24 oilfields in the eastern part of the South
China Sea have become operational, and one more is expected to
begin operation within a few months.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the eastern South China Sea, the country's
largest crude oil production base, generated 11.84 million tons of
in 1996. Total deposits in the area could reach five billion tons,
only 10 percent of which has so far been found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
