<HEADLINE> South Korean President's Son Gets 3-Year Prison Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam's second son, Kim Hyun-chul, was sentenced to three-year
imprisonment today by the Seoul District Court for charges of tax
evasion and taking bribes.
</P>
<P>
The junior Kim was also ordered to pay a fine of 1.44 billion
won (about 1.6 million U.S. dollars) for tax evasion and an
additional penalty of 524.2 million won (about 582,000
U.S. dollars) for taking bribes from businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Kim, 38, was arrested on May 17 and indicted on June 5, charged
with influence-peddling and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution had earlier demanded that Kim serve seven
years' imprisonment on charges that he received 6.61 billion won
(about 7.34 million dollars) from six businessmen from 1993 till
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
But the court acquitted Kim of the charge that he received 1.5
billion won (about 1.67 million dollars) from Dooyang Group chairman
Kim Duk-yong through influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
In its judgment, the court condemned Kim Hyun-chul's receipt of
huge amounts of money from the businessmen and tax evasion as
"failing to fulfill his status as the son of the president."
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam formally took his five-year term office
in February, 1993, after he won the presidential election in
1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
