<HEADLINE> Experts Predicts More Alternative Fuel Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Experts attending the ongoing
15th World Petroleum Congress (WPC) predicted here today that the
market share of alternative fuel vehicles will grow in the future.
</P>
<P>
Alternative fuels are a way to reduce dependency on oil and
they can also assist in solving agricultural problems if they are
of renewable resources, Alexander Buchsbaum with the Austria-based
OMV AG said at a forum of the congress.
</P>
<P>
A number of fuels are capable of powering motor vehicles
including ethanol, methanol, esters derived from oil seeds,
electricity, natural gas and liquid petroleum gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Alternative fuels have a number of inherent properties which
make them more environmentally benign than conventional gasoline,
he said.
</P>
<P>
While natural gas vehicles are presently the popular choice
among alternative fuel vehicles, electric vehicles are actually
close to zero emitting, he said.
</P>
<P>
But most of the current alternative fuel vehicles have two
disadvantages, namely higher cost and smaller range, compared to
gasoline and diesel fuel vehicles, Buchsbaum said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, diesel fuel and gasoline will continue to comprise
the main share of automotive fuels, with efforts to be further
made to ensure reliability and safety of them, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Still Respect Local Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Zimbabweans
continue to appreciate traditional music and dances as they
strive to identify themselves with their culture, Cleopas Makoni,
chairman of the Zimbabwe Traditional Dance Association said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the 1997 traditional dances prize-awarding ceremony, Makoni
said the number of people coming to witness the event were
increasing each year as Zimbabweans sought to learn about their
tradition.
</P>
<P>
Although people were exposed to other foreign cultures, he
noted, there was tendency to retreat to one's culture.
</P>
<P>
"Most of our children are exposed to dancehall reggae, pop and
gospel music in urban areas. But whenever there is an event like
this one they always come to watch because they have an itching
desire to know what their elders were doing in the past," Makoni
added.
</P>
<P>
Due to the lack of places where traditional dances are
performed, the association felt obliged to charge no fee for
entry into the annual event to enable people to see the dances.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Education, Sport and Culture Minister Gabriel
Machinga said traditional dances were not only a form of
entertainment but reflected the culture of people which should be
preserved, adding that youths had a lot to learn from the dances.
</P>
<P>
"Youths now have a credit to conduct research on the
traditional dances and write books on them to ensure that they
are preserved," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
