<HEADLINE> Poverty Alleviation Tops Malawian Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili
Muluzi has said that poverty alleviation is the top priority of
his administration, Zambia's leading independent newspaper The
Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Opening parliament Sunday in Lilongwe, Malawi's capital,
Muluzi promised that his government will continue to fight
poverty until it is eradicated.
</P>
<P>
However, lack of enough food is always a problem besetting the
Malawian leaders since food security is one of the most important
indication in poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi disclosed that his country is suffering food shortage
of 288 thousand tons of maize at present, adding the government
has worked out intervention measures to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
At the 17th summit of the Southern African Development
Community held earlier last month, Muluzi called on other members
of the regional grouping for urgent food aid to his country,
which registered a shortfall of 31 percent of food production
compared with the harvest in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Malawi is looking for markets from which to buy the staple
crop, said the president, who came to power in Malawi's first
multi-party polls in 1994 and promised to maintain democracy and
fight to end mass poverty in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Malawi, which has an area of 118.5 thousand square kilometers
and a population of 10 million, is classified by the United
Nations as one of the most under-developed countries in the
world.
</P>
<P>
To eradicate the widespread poverty in Malawi, the Muluzi
government formulated the program for poverty alleviation in
1995. But weak economic infrastructure and frequent natural
disasters have made the president's ambition impossible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Chakma Refugees to be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The repatriation of Chakma
refugees, now sheltered in six refugee camps in the Indian state
of Tripura, will resume next month following more benefits offered
by the Bangladeshi government, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The refugees took shelter in Tripura in April, 1986 following
disturbances in their hometown Chittagong Hill Tracts due to
decades of war between government forces and pro-independent
Chakma rebels.
</P>
<P>
There were three earlier phases of repatriation on February of
1994, June of 1994 and March of 1997 during which a total of
12,300 Chakma refugees returned to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The decision to resume the process of repatriation was taken
after a visit to Dhaka last month by a delegation of Chakma
leaders, who met Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina in a
dramatic move to end the stalemate regarding the repatriation on
September 12.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has reportedly assured the refugee
delegation that all the conditions agreed upon by the government,
including the return of their land and homestead, would be fully
implemented and some additional benefits would be provided to the
returnees.
</P>
<P>
The additional benefits include the extension of free ration
for the returnees from nine months to one year and a financial
grant of 10,000 taka (about 250 U.S. dollars) to each of the
family of the tribesman killed in different incidents.
</P>
<P>
About 44,000 refugees are still left in the six refugees camps
in India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WPC to Release New Petroleum Definitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A new set of definitions
standardizing international concepts governing crude oil and reserves
will be issued by the World Petroleum Congress (WPC) here tomorrow,
Xinhua was told here today.
</P>
<P>
The 15th World Petroleum Congress, opened here yesterday, will
make adjustments in the original standards in conjunction with the
Society of Petroleum Engineers, according to Paul Tempest, director
general of the WPC.
</P>
<P>
The old definitions, established by the first WPC in 1933, fail
to reflect new technology and the diversity of geological
environments in which oil and gas are now produced, Tempest said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the alterations now will help the international
business circle to have a clearer understanding of current
petroleum production that varies from place to place.
</P>
<P>
The changes will reflect the neutrality that has been the WPC's
consistent policy, Tempest said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
