<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exxon Predicts Growing Oil Demand in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- International petroleum giant
Exxon forecast here today that demand of oil for transportation and
industrial use in Asia will grow by nearly 10 million barrels per
day by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Lee Raymond, chairman and chief executive officer of the
U.S.-based company, told the ongoing 15th World Petroleum Congress
that the growth in Asia's oil demand will be equivalent to about 40
new large refineries over the period.
</P>
<P>
Energy use and economic growth are inextricably linked, Raymond
said. "The countries with the highest economic growth and the
highest standards of living are also those with the highest energy
use per capita," he said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the energy comes from fossil fuels at present,
accounting for about 85 percent both in Asia and in the world as a
whole, Raymond said, adding that oil and natural gas supply the
majority in energy consumption, with coal also being a major player.
</P>
<P>
"With no readily available economic alternatives on the horizon,
fossil fuels will continue to supply most of the world's and this
region's energy for the foreseeable future," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In recognition of this, we must continue to develop and apply
technology and expertise that enable us to use fossil fuels in ways
that are efficient and environmentally sound," he said.
</P>
<P>
Doing that will require a great deal, from both government and
the petroleum industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
Raymond noted that supply strategies are changing, with Chinese
and other Asian companies becoming more active in exploration in
other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"But this change should not cause us to lose sight of the need
to maintain and, if possible, increase local production and
reserves," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Asia still has numerous areas with hydrocarbon potential. But
it will take a major effort to unlock these resources for the
benefit of consumers," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
