<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Arms Deal with Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's state arms
exporter Denel has denied the reports that it was selling or
planning to sell any military equipment to Algeria.
</P>
<P>
This followed reports carried in the Sunday Independent
yesterday which claimed that Denel had clinched a number of
seeker remotely piloted surveillance aircrafts.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today quoted a Denel spokesman as saying his
company "was not selling anything to Algeria".
</P>
<P>
The seeker remotely piloted surveillance system is designed to
be sent behind enemy lines from where it sends back
high-resolution video pictures of enemy installations and troop
and vehicle movements.
</P>
<P>
The system is usually sold with a launch vehicle and a station
from where a pilot can remotely control it.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Independent said the Algerian government would use
the equipment in their fight against "Islamic extremists".
</P>
<P>
The deal was said to have followed the visit to South Africa
last week by a delegation of senior officials of the Algerian
defense force to view local weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian ambassador in Pretoria Sadek Kitoumi reportedly
told the local press that joint-venture deals with South African
defense companies were possible, but Algeria would "not order any
lethal weapons from South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
