<HEADLINE> Uganda Requests Kenya to Open Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Syluester Wanjusi-Wasieba,
Uganda's State Minister for Works, Transport and Communications,
and other local officials have asked Kenya to open Lwakhakha
border post, local daily The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
The request was conveyed to Wilfred Ndolo, head of the 33-man
delegation from Kenya who were having a one-day visit in Mbale,
eastern Uganda last week.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan official asked the Kenya side to revive trade
across Lwakhakha border.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries need each other, more so the local people
living on either side of the border. There is a bumper harvest of
maize and beans in Mbale and the commodities are greatly needed
in Kenya, why not open the border to allow in these exports,"
Wanjusi inquired.
</P>
<P>
He warned that further closure of the border post would
encourage smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Ndolo, however, explained that the recent IMF and World Bank
withdrawal of funding to Kenya had disrupted the budget, which
meant "Fund for such projects like construction of offices and
accommodation for customs officials, police and repair of roads
and offices at Lwakhakha, were diverted to other areas." 
</P>
</TEXT>
