<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Output, Reserves Expected to Grow Steadily (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China's crude oil production
will keep increasing steadily over the next decade, a senior
Chinese official said here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the country's oil demand can be met by domestic
production, Wang Tao, senior advisor to the China National
Petroleum Corporation, said at the ongoing 15th World Petroleum
Congress.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country with 1.2 billion people, "China must be
committed to the development and utilization of its own domestic
hydrocarbon resources," Wang said, adding that it's "the base of
the state petroleum strategy".
</P>
<P>
China produced 157 million tons of crude oil and 20.1 billion
cubic meters of natural gas last year. Net oil imports accounted
for eight percent of domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Wang forecast that China's annual oil demand will rise to 195
million tons in 2000 and 265 million tons in 2010.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has a promising future to meet its own needs
mainly by promoting domestic oil and gas production in the coming
years, based on the achievements made for oil and gas exploration
and development as well as estimates of reserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
