<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Output, Reserves Expected to Grow Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Figures show that the ultimate recoverable oil resources in
China, in line with the world prevailing standards, total 102
billion barrels. By the end of 1996, the cumulative proved
recoverable oil reserves were 38 billion barrels, with the rest
yet to be proved.
</P>
<P>
China also has abundant non-conventional oil resources, such as
extra-heavy oil, bitumen and oil shales, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The oil shale resources alone account for 483.1 billion tons,
among which 31.1 billion tons is composed of more than five
percent oil content.
</P>
<P>
The oil production in China is increasing steadily, Wang said,
and "very good prospects" are foreseeable as a result of increased
exploration and enhanced oil recovery activities in existing
matured oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil production in east China contributes to 75 percent of
the national total. Wang said that the recoverable reserves in the
region have been increasing by 700 million barrels each year, as
new geophysical methods have been applied.
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that in the coming decade, additional
recoverable oil reserves will be found and oil output will be
almost the same as today in this part of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He regarded west China as the country's strategic area for oil
production, noting that significant exploration breakthroughs have
been made in Tarim, Junggar and Turpan-Hami basins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
