<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Output, Reserves Expected to Grow Steadily (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The cumulative proved recoverable oil reserves in west China
reached 4.93 billion barrels and the daily oil production was
396,000 barrels by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"In the couple of years later, a dramatic increase over the
current figures can be expected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wang described offshore China as having "huge
potential" in hydrocarbon resources, noting that the recoverable
resources total about 21 billion barrels at present and will
increase further as more exploration and development will be made
in Bohai Sea and South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
The daily oil production from offshore has been greatly
increased from 25,400 barrels in 1990 to 300,000 barrels in 1996,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the national total of gas production will keep
increasing in the coming decade. Wang forecast that the annual
output of natural gas will reach 25 to 30 billion cubic meters in
2000 and 60 to 80 billion cubic meters in 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
