<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Countries Urged to Mobilize Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPPUR, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today called upon the Asia-Pacific countries to
mobilize financial resources from within instead of relying on
multilateral and bilateral donors in their efforts to eradicate
poverty.
</P>
<P>
A proposal by the Regional Steering Committee on the Economic
Advancement of Rural and Island Women for the Asia-Pacific
(RSC-AP) for an independent national revolving fund could be
utilized as an alternative to multilateral, multi-donor
international funds intended to assist the poor, he said at an
RSC-AP meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
The RSC-AP, dedicated to poverty eradication among women in the
region, made the proposal in April this year for setting up such a
fund as the most crucial measure towards achieving its goal in
reaching 70 million poor women in the Asia Pacific region with
poverty-focused Micro-Finance Institutions (MFIs) by 2005.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the mobilization of financial resources from
within our own nations should be the first step towards
self-reliance and gaining dignity for indigenous ways of
generating funds," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that it was more appropriate to be self-reliant
than depending on rich countries and that the nations of the
RSC-AP could collectively mobilize resources without the need to
be overdependent on developed economies.
</P>
<P>
He said "I believe that through concerted efforts and
commitments from non-governmental organizations and the private
sectors, we can create the greatest social development engineering
for the poor in the next century."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the banking sector, governments and MFIs should
work together towards creating a supportive national policy
framework for the creation of an environment for MFIs to be
nurtured into financially viable and sustainable institutions.
</P>
<P>
The six-day RSC-AP meeting which started on October 11 is being
attended by representatives from 14 RSC-AP members -- Australia,
China, India, Indonesia, Iran, Kazakhstan, Maldives, Malaysia,
Pakistan, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Tonga, Uzbekistan and
Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
