<HEADLINE> Tibet Largest Habitat for Snub-Nosed Monkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Markam county in southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region has become the world's largest
habitat for Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys, with more than 700 of the
primates.
</P>
<P>
The population a decade ago was 600, according to the forestry
department of the autonomous region. The world's population of
snub-nosed monkeys is about 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The species was thought to live only in Yunnan province, where
its name derived, but in 1988 an expedition discovered that the
actual main habitat for the monkeys is an area with a north-south
length of about 200 kilometers and a east-west width of less than
40 kilometers spanning Deqin county of Yunnan and Markam of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the Markam Nature Reserve was established. The
reserve, with a land area of 1,853 square kilometers, has 880
square kilometers set aside for the snub-nosed monkeys.
</P>
<P>
The Forestry Survey Institute experts of the autonomous
region's forestry department say the main threat to the snub-nosed
monkeys comes from forest fires and hunters from outside the area.
</P>
<P>
The population of snub-nosed monkeys in Markam is expected to
surpass 1,000 in a not too long period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
