<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, German FMs Co-pen Article on Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and his German counterpart Klaus
Kinkel have co-penned an article to mark the 25th anniversary of
the establishment of diplomatic relationship between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The article, which was published today in the People's Daily,
said that the idea of publishing a joint article came to the two
ministers when they met in New York on September 25 during the
52nd U.N. General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers hailed the establishment of diplomatic
relationship between the People's Republic of China and the
Federal Republic of Germany on October 11, 1972 as an event of
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
Over the past quarter of a century, the article said, the
speed, depth and range of the development of Sino-German
cooperation have been unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
High-ranking officials of the two countries frequently
exchanged visits while multi-leveled coordination and cooperation
mechanisms were set up in all government departments.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits between heads of state and government of
the two countries contributed a great deal to deepening mutual
understanding and promoting bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Sino-German economic ties and trade keep growing, with Germany
being China's biggest trade partner in Europe, the article said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, bilateral trade exceeded 20 billion Deutsche marks
(11.4 billion U.S. dollars), trebling that of the year when
diplomatic relationship was established between China and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that Germany is also the biggest technology
exporter to China in Europe. By now, Germany has invested in more
than 1,500 projects in China, mainly in transportation,
communications, energy and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Financial and technological cooperation is also very
successful, the article said. Germany has more than 160
development aid projects in China.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also noted that China and Germany are opening
up new forms and fields for cooperation while strengthening
traditional cooperation in trade.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation and exchange have also expanded in the fields of
science and technology, education, culture and environmental
protection, forming an exchange pattern of multi-levels, channels,
fields and forms.
</P>
<P>
They noted that in 1997, a high-tech dialogue forum was
established, while colleges and universities as well as
professional training schools in both countries saw sound
development of cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
Non-governmental communication is diversified in form and rich
in content. There have been 34 pairs of sister cities and
provinces in China and Germany. Direct cultural communication is
very active between them.
</P>
<P>
Germany is one of China's major partners in Europe. Germany and
China share the same or similar views on many major international
issues. They maintain close consultation and smooth cooperation on
issues such as the anti-nuclear and bio-chemical proliferation
campaign, anti-drug campaign, environmental protection and
disarmament, the article said.
</P>
<P>
China gives its backing to the unification of Europe and the
integration process of the European Union, and hopes to see
Germany playing a greater role in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and people always extend their sympathy,
understanding and support to the reunification of the two Germanys.
</P>
<P>
For Germany, China occupies the central place in its Asia
policy. The German government upholds its One China policy and
always supports the reform and opening-up policies adopted by the
Chinese government in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Germany also gives strong backing to China's application for
the membership of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers said Germany and China have
differences with regard to some issues because they have different
social systems, cultures, ideologies, values and levels of
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The existence of such differences is only normal for a
diversified world, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The article said during their meeting in September last year,
they stressed state-to-state relationship should be based on the
principles of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit and they
agreed that despite their differences on the human rights issue, a
solution should be found through dialogue, not confrontation, on
the basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Friendship and cooperation between Germany and China during the
past 25 years are crucial not only for the interests of the two
peoples but also the promotion of world peace and economic
development, the article said.
</P>
<P>
There exists a bright future for long-term, stable cooperation
between a reforming and opening China with rapid economic growth
and a reunified and powerful Germany.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Kinkel said that they believed the German and Chinese
people would join efforts to establish a fair and rational
international political and economic order and to help build a
better world in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
