<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in Czech Republic Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in the
Czech Republic rose to 4.8 percent in September, up 1.6 percentage
points over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs reported today that
registered unemployment at the end of September totaled nearly
250,000, a record high in eight years.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that unemployment will continue to rise,
likely to cap five percent by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The rise in unemployment was primarily due to the austerity
measures the government took in April and May to cope with the
serious economic difficulties. Spending budget was drastically
cut, followed by staff reductions in enterprises and institutions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rise, the Czech Republic remains one of the East
European countries with the lowest unemployment rate. In 1996, its
jobless rate was 3.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
