<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Joint Venture Taps 50 Million Tons of Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese-Russian oil and
gas joint venture, Vietsovpetro, has tapped 50 million tons of oil
from Vietnam's southern continental shelf by Sunday morning, the
Vietnam Oil and Gas Corporation (Petrovietnam) announced.
</P>
<P>
Vietsovpetro, founded in 1981, began exploiting the Bach Ho
(white tiger) Oilfield in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The company has been one of the most profitable enterprises in
the country and earned Vietnam more than 3.4 billion U.S. dollars
in revenue in the past six years and nine months.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, producing 26,000-27,000 tons of crude oil
daily, exploited 6.9 million tons of crude oil in the first nine
months or 76.7 percent of its 1997 target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
