<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Economic Officials Begin Meeting in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUBANG JAYA (MALAYSIA), October 13 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN senior
economic officials began their two-day meeting here today to
prepare for the 29th ASEAN Economic Ministers (AEM) meeting from
October 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
The Senior Economic Officials Meeting (SEOM) would focus on the
progress of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) and top officials
from the trade and industry ministries of the ASEAN countries
would fine-tune commitments by the respective members to tearing
down tariffs, meeting sources said.
</P>
<P>
The AEM is considered significant for the implementation of
AFTA and thus the region's resolve to create an attractive single
free market where tariffs would be between only zero and 5 percent
by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Economic ministers from Laos and Myanmar, which were admitted
into the regional grouping last July at the 30th ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting, would for the first time attend the AEM which is
scheduled to be opened by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
What is noteworthy is the fact that the AEM comes at a time
when the ASEAN economies, especially that of Indonesia, the
Philippines, Thailand and host Malaysia, are being severely tested
due to what are described as manipulative and speculative attacks
on their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is expected to propose for the AEM to consider,
possibly, common strategies to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
