<HEADLINE> Taliban Suffer Losses in North Afghanistan: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
have conceded the loss of ground near their northern opposition's
stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a senior Taliban leader, Mulla Wakil Ahmad,
as saying the militia had lost Tashkurgan, a strategically located
town in the northern province of Samangan. The town is situated
about 50 kilometers east of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the anti-Taliban alliance was also quoted
as saying no resistance was put up when their forces entered
Tashkurgan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reports said forces of the alliance had launched
simultaneous attacks against the Taliban in northern Kunduz
Province and captured several districts.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban were in deep trouble after the forces of northern
warlord Rashid Dostum entered the province from the west while the
fighters of former Defense Minister Ahmad Masood moved in from the
east, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The gains for the opposition have relieved the Taliban pressure
on Mazar-e-Sharif, the only Afghan city not held by the Taliban,
which has been under sustained attack for one month, the reports
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
