<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Begins First South America Trip in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
arrived here today to start his first South America trip, aiming
to strengthen trade with that part of America.
</P>
<P>
Clinton chose October 12, the Columbus Day, as the day to start
his tour. The day is a common holiday celebrated in most of the
North and South American countries for the discovery of Columbus
some 500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In his speech upon arrival, Clinton called for unity of
American countries and appraised the free market economies of the
South American countries and their efforts on eliminating trade
barriers and multiplying employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera said Venezuela and the
United States "have a ... joint commitment against corruption,
against delinquency, against drug trafficking."
</P>
<P>
Venezuela is the United States' biggest oil supplier. Some 70
percent of Venezuelan oil enter into the U.S. market. From January
to September this year, the country exported 1.7 million barrels
of oil to the United States every day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States becomes Venezuela's biggest trade
partner. In 1996, bilateral trade amounted to 17.2 billion
U.S. dollars, accounting for more than half of the country's total
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
During his 24-hour visit here, Clinton will hold talks with
Caldera on customs, environmental protection, technological
cooperation and especially energy issues.
</P>
<P>
He was accompanied by Energy Secretary Federico Pena, Commerce
Secretary William Daley and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
as well as U.N. Ambassador Bill Richardson and the drug policy
adviser, General Barry McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is the fourth U.S. president who has visited Venezuela,
following John Kennedy in 1961, Jimmy Carter in 1978 and George
Bush in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will also visit Brazil and Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
