<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Project Started in Sri Lanka's Ancient City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 13 (Xinhua) -- A project has been started to
ease water shortage in Sri Lanka's ancient city of Anuradhapura in
North Central Province.
</P>
<P>
The cost of 54 million U.S. dollars of the project came from
the French government, the Asian Development Bank and the Sri
Lankan government, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project, when completed, could increase daily water supply
capacity from the present 8.34 million liters to 20.82 million
liters by year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Lack of rains and high evaporation rate make the shortage of
water a serious problem for the old town.
</P>
<P>
Anuradhapura was made the first capital of the ancient Sri
Lankan kingdom around 380 B.C. Though only the ruins of the old
glories have survived, the city remains a sacred place for
Buddhists to pay their homage to the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
People gather here in large numbers in the pilgrimage season
each year, boosting the population of Anuradhapura from around
60,000 to 600,000 seasonally and further worsening the water
supply situation there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
