<HEADLINE> Thai Developers Long for Japanese Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Developers of Thailand's
industrial estates are hoping that more Japanese investment will
come as a result of Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's Japan
visit last week.
</P>
<P>
Sales of land in industrial estates were lackluster in recent
months because both domestic and foreign businessmen are delaying
investment, according to Thavich Dechavanakul, secretary-general
of the Thai Industrial Estate Developers Association.
</P>
<P>
Investors are waiting for the baht, the country's currency, as
well as the general political and economic situation, to
stabilize.
</P>
<P>
The value of the baht, now fluctuating around 36 to the U.S.
dollar, has depreciated about 40 percent against the greenback
since its flotation on July 2.
</P>
<P>
As a result of investors' wait-and-see attitude, large tracks
of land in the estates are unsold.
</P>
<P>
Developers hope that Chavalit's visit to Japan last week will
help restore confidence among Japanese investors and induce them
to move their ventures to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
If no businesses move into the estates within the next three
months, many developers will have to scrap their projects, Thavich
was quoted by the local press today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thavich is confident that the Japanese will step in to help
rescue Thailand's economy because they have been doing business in
the country for a long time and regard the country as a key
production base.  
</P>
</TEXT>
