<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Enhance Cooperation with World Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- China looks forward to further
developing the cooperative relations with the world oil industry
on the basis of equality and mutual benefit, a senior Chinese
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tao, senior advisor to the China National Petroleum
Corporation, said at the 15th World Petroleum Congress that China
is willing to enhance cooperation with both developed and
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation will be conducted in line with international
practice and in flexible forms that can be accepted by all
partners, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities for cooperation exist in the fields of oil
recovery, downstream processing, long-distance oil and gas
pipeline construction, research and development as well as human
resources training, he said.
</P>
<P>
More foreign capital and advanced technologies as well as
managerial skills are also welcome, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese oil industry has been expanding cooperation with
international partners since 1978, with close ties with the world
petroleum community already in place.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, offshore exploration was first open for international
cooperation. To date, some 126 petroleum contracts and agreements
with a total investment of 5.38 billion US dollars have been
signed with 67 companies from 18 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the cooperation has brought advanced foreign
technologies and managerial skills to the Chinese offshore oil
industry, helping offshore oil production keep on increasing at an
average annual rate of 39.6 percent for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
As for onshore petroleum international cooperation, 37
contracts valued at one billion U.S. dollars have been signed
since 1985, in addition to five billion U.S. dollars of foreign
credit loans in the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
In the process of opening to the outside world, China now has
started to play an active role in overseas petroleum exploration
and development, Wang said, adding that a couple of petroleum
contracts have been signed with countries including Peru, Sudan,
Venezuela, Khazakstan, Canada and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The rather complicated geological conditions in China have
helped the industry accumulate rich working experience and it also
trained a group of qualified experts as well as a strong work
force, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to share our technologies and experience with
the world, particularly with developing countries by multiple ways
and means," he said. "We will keep on developing ties with some
countries for oil import and export business to improve oil and
gas supply of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese petroleum industry will strengthen
cooperation with its neighboring countries as the acceleration of
hydrocarbon exploration and development is of great significance
to the balance between supply and demand in the Asia-Pacific
region as well as the world market, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese oil industry is willing to join hands with its
counterparts and work hard to develop a more prosperous world
petroleum industry in the 21st century," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0219 </DOCNO>
