<HEADLINE> WB Loans Aid Yantai Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Yantai, the coastal city of
East China's Shandong Province solved acute housing shortages in
its enterprises by introducing the World Bank loans, today's
"China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
To date, the World Bank loans have helped nearly 500 workers to
move into new homes. From December 1995 to August 1997, more than
32,600 square meters of living space were allotted to enterprises
in the city built with the help of the loans, with 100,000 sq m to
be available for occupancy by the end of the year, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the World Bank approved a loan of 330 million US
dollars to four major Chinese cities, including Yantai, Beijing,
Chengdu and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, the city leading the way in the nationwide housing
reform, along recieved 400,000 US dollars to reform the current
residential systems of its enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The low-cost housing projects aided by WB loans was
well-received among Yantai enterprises, and 43 of them
participated in the project with a total of 680,000 square meters
of living space, and 100,000 square meters of new housing is given
to these enterprises each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
