<HEADLINE> Italian Police Detain Activist for Drug Distribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- A leading Italian political
activist was arrested today in downtown Rome when she tried to
hand out packets of hashish during a rally calling for the
legalization of light drugs.
</P>
<P>
"I denounce myself for violating the law on drugs and for
association to commit crime," Rita Bernardini, 45, a key member of
the right-wing Radical Party, said as she finished her speech and
attempted to distribute to demonstrators some 400 envelopes each
containing one-half gram of hashish.
</P>
<P>
Police immediately stepped onto the podium and took her into
custody.
</P>
<P>
Italian law on drugs permits small quantities to be held for
personal consumption, but punishes handing it to others harshly as
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Anti-prohibitionists have long been agitating for the law to
distinguish between relatively harmless light drugs such as
hashish and others like heroin.
</P>
<P>
Bernardini is part of a political movement headed by Marco
Panella, who was given a suspended eight-month jail sentence on
September 19 for a public distribution of hashish and marijuana in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Panella's Radical Party became known for frequently creating
media events to propagandize its cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
