<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeological Finds In West China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists recently
unearthed a bone artifact and other 30,000 Neolithic relics,
mostly painted pottery.
</P>
<P>
They were discovered at 300 tombs at the Zongri site in Tongde
County, Qinghai province. One unique painted pottery basin has a
design of two men carrying something.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists had already found bronze age relics in
Shangtao in Datong county and Shenna in the city of Xining.
</P>
<P>
In Shenna, they began to unravel a mystery of the Qijia Culture
when they found a large number of dwellings and cave ruins and a
large bronze spear that is very rare.
</P>
<P>
Many unusual finds also came from four tombs of the Eastern Han
Dynasty (25-220 A. D.) that had been spared destruction by tomb
robbers. The unearthed tombs provide information about customs of
the time, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
Relics found in tombs in the Qaidam Basin in northwest China
and Central Asia have proven the close links between China and
neighboring kingdoms in ancient times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971013.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
