<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Police Fail to Stem Flow of Ecstasy Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's anti-narcotics
police are fighting a losing battle against the influx of ecstasy
drugs because certain senior officials are working together with
the traffickers, a drug enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
Ecstasy drugs were widespread at popular entertainment places
and hotels, Narcotics Suppression Bureau Commissioner Noppadol
Somboonsap was quoted today by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite hard work, police could arrest only minor traffickers
as the major ones had been tipped off by well-known senior
officials with access to inside information obtained by police
intelligence, he said.
</P>
<P>
"What we have seized is less than 10 percent of all ecstasy
tablets available in the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the commissioner, ecstasy drugs are mostly
transported by air from Europe through Singapore to Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
