<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 13 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The last and largest national sports gala of the century,
the Eighth National Games, started in Shanghai yesterday. Top
Party and government officials including president Jian Zemin as
well as Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the International
Olympic Committee, attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
-- The 15th World Petroleum Congress opened in Beijing
yesterday. President Jian Zemin made an opening speech at the
meeting in which he expressed confidence that China is able to
stabilize and increase domestic oil and gas output.
</P>
<P>
-- China is currently hosting the 23rd General Population
Conference of the International Union for Scientific Study of
Population in Beijing. Premier Li Peng said in his speech
yesterday that co-ordination of population control with the
economy, society, resources and the environment is the only option
in the modernization of China.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The Sate Education Commission and the State Statistics
Bureau revealed yesterday that the total expenditure of the
country's education fund in 1996 reached 226 billion yuan, up
20.47 percent from the previous year. The national financial
education expenditure made up 2.44 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP), up 0.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Liaoning Province in northeast China pledged to improve the
performace of its state-run enterprises within next three
years. The provincial authorities have worked out ten concrete
measures to facilitate the realization of the goal.
</P>
<P>
 China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China's top sports official Wu Shaozu said that China is yet
to decide whether to launch another bid to host the Olympic Games
after the Eighth National Games and Shanghai might step in as the
second Chinese city to submit such an application.
</P>
<P>
-- China's conformity assessment system is noticeably improving
quality management and product quality while winning increasing
international recognition.
</P>
<P>
-- China will intensify the enforcement of environmental
protection measures over the next few years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
