<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judo Worlds Conclude in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 12 (Xinhua) -- China won a bronze medal on the
last day of the the World Judo Championships that concluded here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Hua, 21, beat her Romanian and Polish opponents on her way
to taking the bronze in the women's open class competition.
</P>
<P>
She lost to Cuba's Dai Nabeltran, the eventual winner of the
event, in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
eltran overcame Raquel Barrientos of Spain to take the
crown. Barrientos carried home the silver.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's other events, Japan collected two victories with
Ryoko Tamura easily winning the women's under-48 kg title at the
expense of Cuban Amarillis Savon.
</P>
<P>
Tadahiro Nomura was equally impressive in his victory over
Georgian George Revazishvili in the men's under 60-kg category.
</P>
<P>
Poland's Rafael Kubacki beat Japan's Yoshiharu Makishi to win
the men's open category.
</P>
<P>
France and Japan each collected four golds at these
championships, followed by South Korea with three.
</P>
<P>
Poland pocketed two golds while Britain, Spain and Cuba each
got one.
</P>
<P>
China only won three bronzes, two from women's events and one
from men's.
</P>
<P>
The event was attended by over 700 athletes from 100 countries
and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
