<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 28 Detained and 69 Injured in World Cup Disorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Police said here today that 24
Britons and four Italians were detained, 33 Britons and 36
Italians injured disorders in Rome before, during and after
yesterday evening's World Cup game in which England won access to
the final phase of the competition in France Next year.
</P>
<P>
Officials at Rome's police headquarters said charges had been
preferred against 14 Britons and two Italians. Only one of the
injured, Paul Shadbolt, was reported in a serious condition. He
was knifed in the stomach and doctors fear he may have suffered
internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, the charges range from aggravated
disorder and insulting behaviour to causing bodily harm and
resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
Before the game, police made baton charges against rioting fans
around the Spanish Steps and other parts of downtown Rome. There
were also baton charges in the areas of the stands reserved to the
English fans. After the match, three buses and three trams were
damaged.
</P>
<P>
Police intervened in the stands when Italian and English fans
started hurling objects at each other. A cordon of baton-wielding
agents separated them and later charged to push back the English
fans twenty or so yards. The incidents stirred up polemics and
rispostes in Rome and London, where returning fans claimed their
Italian confreres had behaved "like animals".
</P>
<P>
In London, Davis Mellor, the Tory ex-minister who heads
Britain's official soccer commission, charged the Italian police
with "over-reacting", and the FA's executive director Graham Kelly
criticised the Italian organisers of the event.
</P>
<P>
The police chief reported that the 6,000 England fans involved
were escorted from the stadium first, loaded into sixty municipal
buses and left at scattered points around the city, which
prevented incidents during the night.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of fans were detained and in some cases charged in
incidents in various parts of Italy as the England supporters
converged on Rome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
