<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Premier John Olsen of South Australia state faces forming a
minority government after South Australian voters savaged his
deeply divided liberals in an historic election upset.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- More than 60,000 multi-colored plastic hands were planted on
the lawns of the Parliament House yesterday by the Australians for
Native Title and Reconciliation, an independent organization, as a
display of support for aboriginal reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer will appeal to
the Malaysian government to reconsider Australia's bid for a 1.4
billion U.S. dollar naval patrol boat contract, which is believed
to have gone to a German bidder.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The pay-TV merger between Australis Media and Foxtel is
expected to be blocked today by the Australian Competition and
Consumer Commission, undermining federal government hopes of a
smooth passage for the 10.2 billion U.S. dollar telecommunications
giant Telstra float.  
</P>
