<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camerounians Go to Polls to Elect New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, October 12 (Xinhua) -- Camerounians today went to
polling stations throughout the nation's territory to elect a new
president who will lead the country for the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
Candidates of seven political parties including the ruling
Cameroun People's Democratic Movement (CPDM) are vying for the
post of the president of the republic.
</P>
<P>
In the nation's capital Yaounde, most of the polling stations
opened at 8:00 a.m. as stipulated by the law. The election day in
the capital today went on smoothly without any incident recorded,
and some of the earlier voters were seen coming to vote at 9:00
a.m.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent President and candidate of the CPDM Paul Biya cast
his vote at the Government Bilingual Grammar School in Bastos
here this afternoon. Prime Minister Pete Mafany Musonge also cast
his vote in the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Radio Cameroun, presidential election has taken
place throughout all the provinces of the country in peace, order
and tranquillity. But in some places, there were not many voters
to visit polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Since the three major opposition parties -- the Social
Democratic Front (SDF), the National Union for Democracy and
Progress (NUDP) and the Camerounian Democratic Union (CDU) --
declared their boycott of this year's presidential elections,
their militants and sympathizers stayed at home during the
polling day today.
</P>
<P>
Besides, many Camerounians have refused to go to the polls
today, saying their votes would not change anything in the
country, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that only the ruling CPDM party was represented
in all the polling stations throughout Cameroun. Some parties
were eventually absent in all provinces.
</P>
<P>
The polling stations all over the country were expected to be
closed at 6:00 p.m. today. Vote counting is expected to begin
immediately after today's presidential elections. The results
will be officially announced in a few days, perhaps in two weeks,
some said.
</P>
<P>
This is the second presidential election which has taken place
in Cameroun since the multiparty system practiced in the country.
The first presidential election was won by CPDM leader Paul Biya
in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
